(866, 'ajfilavrguroß', 'from (1) (as a negative particle) and (5366)', 'aphilarguros', 'None', 'af-il-ar\'-goo-ros', 'Adjective', 'from «1» (as a negative particle) and «5366»; unavaricious:--without covetousness, not greedy of filthy lucre.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>not loving money, not avaricious</OL>'),
(867, 'a[fixiß', 'from (864)', 'aphixis', 'None', 'af\'-ix-is', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «864»; properly, arrival, i.e. (by implication) departure:--departing.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>arrival<LI>departure</OL>'),
(868, 'ajfivsthmi', 'from (575) and (2476)', 'aphistemi', '1:512,88', 'af-is\'-tay-mee', 'Verb', 'from «575» and «2476»; to remove, i.e. (actively) instigate to revolt; usually (reflexively) to desist, desert, etc.:--depart, draw (fall) away, refrain, withdraw self.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to make stand off, cause to withdraw, to remove<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to excite to revolt</OL><LI>to stand off, to stand aloof<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to go away, to depart from anyone<LI>to desert, withdraw from one<LI>to fall away, become faithless<LI>to shun, flee from<LI>to cease to vex one<LI>to withdraw one\'s self from, to fall away<LI>to keep one\'s self from, absent one\'s self from</OL></OL>'),
(869, 'a[fnw', 'from (852) (contraction)', 'aphno', 'None', 'af\'-no', 'Adverb', 'adverb from «852» (contraction); unawares, i.e. unexpectedly:--suddenly.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>suddenly</OL>'),
(870, 'ajfovbwß', 'from a compound of (1) (as a negative particle) and (5401)', 'aphobos', 'None', 'af-ob\'-oce', 'Adverb', 'adverb from a compound of «1» (as a negative particle) and «5401»; fearlessly:--without fear.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>without fear, boldly</OL>'),
(871, 'ajfomoiovw', 'from (575) and (3666)', 'aphomoioo', '5:198,684', 'af-om-oy-o\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «575» and «3666»; to assimilate closely:--make like.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to cause a model to pass off into an image or shape like it<LI>to express itself in it, to copy<LI>to produce a facsimile<LI>to be made like, render similar</OL>'),
(872, 'ajforavw', 'from (575) and (3708)', 'aphorao', 'None', 'af-or-ah\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «575» and «3708»; to consider attentively:--look.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to turn the eyes away from other things and fix them on something</OL>'),
(873, 'ajforivzw', 'from (575) and (3724)', 'aphorizo', '5:454,728', 'af-or-id\'-zo', 'Verb', 'from «575» and «3724»; to set off by boundary, i.e. (figuratively) limit, exclude, appoint, etc.:--divide, separate, sever.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to mark off from others by boundaries, to limit, to separate<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>in a bad sense: to exclude as disreputable<LI>in a good sense: to appoint, set apart for some purpose</OL></OL>'),
(874, 'ajformhv', 'from a compound of (575) and (3729)', 'aphorme', '5:472,730', 'af-or-may\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'from a compound of «575» and «3729»; a starting-point, i.e. (figuratively) an opportunity:--occasion.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a place from which a movement or attack is made, a base of operations<LI>metaph. that by which endeavour is excited and from which it goes forth<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>that which gives occasion and supplies matter for an undertaking, the incentive<LI>the resources we avail ourselves of in attempting or performing anything</OL></OL>'),
(875, 'ajfrivzw', 'from (876)', 'aphrizo', 'None', 'af-rid\'-zo', 'Verb', 'from «876»; to froth at the mouth (in epilepsy):--foam.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to foam</OL>'),
(876, 'ajfrovß', 'apparently a primary word', 'aphros', 'None', 'af-ros\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'apparently a primary word; froth, i.e. slaver:--foaming.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>foam</OL>'),
(877, 'ajfrosuvnh', 'from (878)', 'aphrosune', '9:220,1277', 'af-ros-oo\'-nay', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «878»; senselessness, i.e. (euphemistically) egotism; (morally) recklessness:--folly, foolishly(-ness).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>foolishness, folly, senselessness<LI>thoughtlessness, recklessness</OL>'),
(878, 'a[frwn', 'from (1) (as a negative particle) and (5424)', 'aphron', '9:220,1277', 'af\'-rone', 'Adjective', 'from «1» (as a negative particle) and «5424»; properly, mindless, i.e. stupid, (by implication) ignorant, (specially) egotistic, (practically) rash, or (morally) unbelieving:--fool(-ish), unwise.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>without reason<LI>senseless, foolish, stupid<LI>without reflection or intelligence, acting rashly</OL>'),
(879, 'ajfupnovw', 'from a compound of (575) and (5258)', 'aphupnoo', '8:545,1233', 'af-oop-no\'-o', 'Verb', 'from a compound of «575» and «5258»; properly, to become awake, i.e. (by implication) to drop (off) in slumber:--fall asleep.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to awaken from sleep<LI>to fall asleep, to fall off to sleep</OL>'),
(880, 'a[fwnoß', 'from (1) (as a negative particle) and (5456)', 'aphonos', 'None', 'af\'-o-nos', 'Adjective', 'from «1» (as a negative particle) and «5456»; voiceless, i.e. mute (by nature or choice); figuratively, unmeaning:--dumb, without signification.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>voiceless, dumb<LI>without faculty of speech<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of idols</OL></OL>'),
(881, 'ÅAcavz', 'of Hebrew origin (0271)', 'Achaz', 'None', 'akh-adz\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Hebrew origin («0271»); Achaz, an Israelite:--Achaz.', 'Ahaz = \"possessor\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the eleventh king of Judah, son of Jotham</OL>'),
(882, 'ÅAcai?a', 'of uncertain derivation', 'Achaia', 'None', 'ach-ah-ee\'-ah', 'Noun Location', 'of uncertain derivation; Achaia (i.e. Greece), a country of Europe:--Achaia.', 'Achaia = \"trouble\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>in a restricted sense, the maritime region of northern Peloponnesus<LI>in a broader sense, a Roman province embracing all Greece except Thessaly</OL>'),
(883, 'ÅAcai>kovß', 'from (882)', 'Achaikos', 'None', 'ach-ah-ee-kos\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «882»; an Achaian; Achaicus, a Christian:--Achaicus.', 'Achaicus = \"belonging to Achaia\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the name of a Christian in Corinth</OL>'),
(884, 'ajcavristoß', 'from (1) (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of (5483)', 'acharistos', '9:372,1298', 'ach-ar\'-is-tos', 'Adjective', 'from «1» (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of «5483»; thankless, i.e. ungrateful:--unthankful.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>ungracious<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>unpleasing<LI>unthankful</OL></OL>'),
(885, 'ÅAcivm', 'probably of Hebrew origin cf (03137)', 'Acheim', 'None', 'akh-ime\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'probably of Hebrew origin (compare «03137»); Achim, an Israelite:--Achim.', 'Achim = \"the Lord will establish\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>one of the ancestors of Christ, his name is not mentioned in the OT</OL>'),
(886, 'ajceiropoivhtoß', 'from (1) (as a negative particle) and (5499)', 'acheiropoietos', '9:436,1309', 'akh-i-rop-oy\'-ay-tos', 'Adjective', 'from «1» (as a negative particle) and «5499»; unmanufactured, i.e. inartificial:--made without (not made with) hands.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>not made with hands</OL>'),
(887, 'ajcluvß', 'of uncertain derivation', 'achlus', 'None', 'akh-looce\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'of uncertain derivation; dimness of sight, i.e. (probably) a cataract:--mist.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>mist, dimness</OL>'),
(888, 'ajcrei\'oß', 'from (1) (as a negative particle) and a derivative of (5534) [cf (5532)]', 'achreios', 'None', 'akh-ri\'-os', 'Adjective', 'from «1» (as a negative particle) and a derivative of «5534» (compare «5532»); useless, i.e. (euphemistically) unmeritorious:--unprofitable.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>useless, good for nothing</OL>'),
(889, 'ajcreiovw', 'from (888)', 'achreioo', 'None', 'akh-ri-o\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «888»; to render useless, i.e. spoil:--become unprofitable.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>make useless, render unserviceable<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of character</OL></OL>'),
(890, 'a[crhstoß', 'from (1) (as a negative particle) and (5543)', 'achrestos', 'None', 'akh\'-race-tos', 'Adjective', 'from «1» (as a negative particle) and «5543»; inefficient, i.e. (by implication) detrimental:--unprofitable.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>useless, unprofitable</OL>'),
(891, 'a[cri', 'akin to (206) (through the idea of a terminus)', 'achri', 'None', 'akh\'-ree', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>until, unto, etc.</OL>', 'or achris akh\'-rece; akin to «206» (through the idea of a terminus); (of time) until or (of place) up to:--as far as, for, in(-to), till, (even, un-)to, until, while. Compare «3360».', ''),
(892, 'a[curon', 'perhaps remotely from cheo (to shed forth)', 'achuron', 'None', 'akh\'-oo-ron', 'Noun Neuter', 'perhaps remotely from cheo (to shed forth); chaff (as diffusive):--chaff.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a stalk of grain from which the kernels have been beaten out<LI>straw broken up by a threshing machine, chaff</OL>'),
(893, 'ajyeudhvß', 'from (1) (as a negative particle) and (5579)', 'apseudes', '9:594,1339', 'aps-yoo-dace\'', 'Adjective', 'from «1» (as a negative particle) and «5579»; veracious:--that cannot lie.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>without lie, truthful</OL>'),
(894, 'a[yinqoß', 'of uncertain derivation', 'apsinthos', 'None', 'ap\'-sin-thos', 'Noun Feminine', 'of uncertain derivation; wormwood (as a type of bitterness, i.e. (figuratively) calamity):--wormwood.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>wormwood<LI>the name of a star which fell into the waters and made them bitter</OL>'),
(895, 'a[yucoß', 'from (1) (as a negative particle) and (5590)', 'apsuchos', 'None', 'ap\'-soo-khos', 'Adjective', 'from «1» (as a negative particle) and «5590»; lifeless, i.e. inanimate (mechanical):--without life.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>without a soul, lifeless</OL>'),
(896, 'Baval', 'of Hebrew origin (01168)', 'Baal', 'None', 'bah\'-al', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Hebrew origin («01168»); Baal, a Phoenician deity (used as a symbol of idolatry):--Baal.', 'Baal = \"lord\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the supreme male divinity of the Phoenician and Canaanitish nations, as Ashtoreth was their supreme female divinity</OL>'),
(897, 'Babulwvn', 'of Hebrew origin (0894)', 'Babulon', '1:514,89', 'bab-oo-lone\'', 'Noun Location', 'of Hebrew origin («0894»); Babylon, the capitol of Chaldaea (literally or figuratively (as a type of tyranny)):-- Babylon.', 'Babylon = \"confusion\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a very large and famous city, the residence of the Babylonian kings, situated on both banks of the Euphrates. Cyrus had formerly captured it, but Darius Hystaspis threw down its gates and walls, and Xerxes destroyed the temple of Belis. At length the city was reduced to almost solitude, the population having been drawn off by the neighbouring Seleucia, built on the Tigris by Seleucus Nicanor.<LI>of the territory of Babylonia<LI>allegorically, of Rome as the most corrupt seat of idolatry and the enemy of Christianity</OL>'),
(898, 'baqmovß', 'from the same as (899)', 'bathmos', 'None', 'bath-mos\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'from the same as «899»; a step, i.e. (figuratively) grade (of dignity):--degree.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>threshold, step<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of a grade of dignity and wholesome influence in the church</OL></OL>'),
(899, 'bavqoß', 'from the same as (901)', 'bathos', '1:517,89', 'bath\'-os', 'Noun Neuter', 'from the same as «901»; profundity, i.e. (by implication) extent; (figuratively) mystery:--deep(-ness, things), depth.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>depth, height<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of \"the deep\" sea<LI>metaph.<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>deep, extreme, poverty<LI>of the deep things of God</OL></OL></OL>'),
(900, 'baquvnw', 'from (901)', 'bathuno', 'None', 'bath-oo\'-no', 'Verb', 'from «901»; to deepen:--deep.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>\'the deep\' sea (the \'high seas\')<LI>deep, extreme poverty, the deep things of God, things hidden and above man\'s scrutiny, especially divine counsels<LI>to make deep</OL>'),
(901, 'baquvß', 'from the base of (939)', 'bathus', 'None', 'bath-oos\'', 'Adjective', 'from the base of «939»; profound (as going down), literally or figuratively:--deep, very early.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>deep</OL>'),
(902, 'bai?on', 'a diminutive of a derivative probably of the base of (939)', 'baion', 'None', 'bah-ee\'-on', 'Noun Neuter', 'a diminutive of a derivative probably of the base of «939»; a palm twig (as going out far):--branch.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a palm branch</OL>'),
(903, 'Balaavm', 'of Hebrew origin (01109)', 'Balaam', '1:524,91', 'bal-ah-am\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Hebrew origin («01109»); Balaam, a Mesopotamian (symbolic of a false teacher):--Balaam.', 'Balaam meaning \"perhaps\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>A native of Pethor a city in Mesopotamia, endued by Jehovah with prophetic power. He was hired by Balak to curse the Israelites; and influenced by the love of reward, he wished to gratify Balak; but he was compelled by Jehovah\'s power to bless them. Hence later the Jews saw him as a most abandoned deceiver.</OL>'),
(904, 'Balavk', 'of Hebrew origin (01111)', 'Balak', 'None', 'bal-ak\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Hebrew origin («01111»); Balak, a Moabite:--Balac.', 'Balak = \"a devastator or spoiler\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a king of Moab</OL>'),
(905, 'ballavntion', 'probably remotely from (906) (as a depository)', 'balantion', '1:525,91', 'bal-an\'-tee-on', 'Noun Neuter', 'probably remotely from «906» (as a depository); a pouch (for money):--bag, purse.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a money bag, purse</OL>'),
(906, 'bavllw', 'a primary word', 'ballo', '1:526,91', 'bal\'-lo', 'Verb', 'a primary verb; to throw (in various applications, more or less violent or intense):--arise, cast (out), × dung, lay, lie, pour, put (up), send, strike, throw (down), thrust. Compare «4496».', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to throw or let go of a thing without caring where it falls<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to scatter, to throw, cast into<LI>to give over to one\'s care uncertain about the result<LI>of fluids<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to pour, pour into of rivers<LI>to pour out</OL></OL><LI>to put into, insert</OL>');
INSERT INTO `greek_lexicon` (`number`, `orig_word`, `word_orig`, `translit`, `tdnt`, `phonetic`, `part_of_speech`, `st_def`, `IPD_def`) VALUES
(907, 'baptivzw', 'from a derivative of (911)', 'baptizo', '1:529,92', 'bap-tid\'-zo', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to dip repeatedly, to immerse, to submerge (of vessels sunk)<LI>to cleanse by dipping or submerging, to wash, to make clean with water, to wash one\'s self, bathe<LI>to overwhelm</OL>Not to be confused with 911, bapto. The clearest example that showsthe meaning of baptizo is a text from the Greek poet and physicianNicander, who lived about 200 B.C. It is a recipe for making picklesand is helpful because it uses both words. Nicander says that inorder to make a pickle, the vegetable should first be \'dipped\'(bapto) into boiling water and then \'baptised\' (baptizo) in thevinegar solution. Both verbs concern the immersing of vegetables in asolution. But the first is temporary. The second, the act ofbaptising the vegetable, produces a permanent change. When used in the New Testament, this word more often refers to ourunion and identification with Christ than to our water baptism. e.g.Mark 16:16. \'He that believes and is baptised shall be saved\'.Christ is saying that mere intellectual assent is not enough. Theremust be a union with him, a real change, like the vegetable to thepickle! Bible Study Magazine, James Montgomery Boice, May 1989.', 'from a derivative of «911»; to immerse, submerge; to make whelmed (i.e. fully wet); used only (in the New Testament) of ceremonial ablution, especially (technically) of the ordinance of Christian baptism:--Baptist, baptize, wash.', ''),
(908, 'bavptisma', 'from (907)', 'baptisma', '1:545,92', 'bap\'-tis-mah', 'Noun Neuter', 'from «907»; baptism (technically or figuratively):--baptism.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>immersion, submersion<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of calamities and afflictions with which one is quite overwhelmed<LI>of John\'s baptism, that purification rite by which men on confessing their sins were bound to spiritual reformation, obtained the pardon of their past sins and became qualified for the benefits of the Messiah\'s kingdom soon to be set up. This was valid Christian baptism, as this was the only baptism the apostles received and it is not recorded anywhere that they were ever rebaptised after Pentecost.<LI>of Christian baptism; a rite of immersion in water as commanded by Christ, by which one after confessing his sins and professing his faith in Christ, having been born again by the Holy Spirit unto a new life, identifies publicly with the fellowship of Christ and the church.</OL></OL>In Rom. 6:3 Paul states we are \"baptised unto death\" meaning that weare not only dead to our former ways, but they are buried. To returnto them is as unthinkable for a Christian as for one to dig up a deadcorpse! In Moslem countries a new believer has little trouble withMoslems until he is publicly baptised. It is then, that the Moslems\'know he means business, and then the persecution starts. See alsodiscussion of baptism under No. 907.'),
(909, 'baptismovß', 'from (907)', 'baptismos', '1:545,92', 'bap-tis-mos\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «907»; ablution (ceremonial or Christian):--baptism, washing.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a washing, purification effected by means of water<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of washing prescribed by the Mosaic law (Heb 9:</OL><LI>which seems to mean an exposition of the difference between the washings prescribed by the Mosaic law and Christian baptism</OL>'),
(910, 'baptisthvß', 'from (907)', 'Baptistes', '1:545,92', 'bap-tis-tace\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «907»; a baptizer, as an epithet of Christ\'s forerunner:--Baptist.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a baptiser<LI>one who administers the rite of baptism<LI>the surname of John, the forerunner of Christ</OL>'),
(911, 'bavptw', 'a primary word', 'bapto', '1:529,92', 'bap\'-to', 'Verb', 'a primary verb; to whelm, i.e. cover wholly with a fluid; in the New Testament only in a qualified or special sense, i.e. (literally) to moisten (a part of one\'s person), or (by implication) to stain (as with dye):--dip.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to dip, dip in, immerse<LI>to dip into dye, to dye, colour</OL>Not to be confused with 907, baptizo. The clearest example that showsthe meaning of baptizo is a text from the Greek poet and physicianNicander, who lived about 200 B.C. It is a recipe for making picklesand is helpful because it uses both words. Nicander says that inorder to make a pickle, the vegetable should first be \'dipped\'(bapto) into boiling water and then \'baptised\' (baptizo) in thevinegar solution. Both verbs concern the immersing of vegetables in asolution. But the first is temporary. The second, the act ofbaptising the vegetable, produces a permanent change.'),
(912, 'Barabba\'ß', 'of Aramaic origin (01247) and (05)', 'Barabbas', 'None', 'bar-ab-bas\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Chaldee origin (1347 and «05»); son of Abba; Bar-abbas, an Israelite:--Barabbas.', 'Barabbas = \"son of a father or master\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the captive robber whom the Jews begged Pilate to release instead of Christ</OL>'),
(913, 'Baravk', 'of Hebrew origin (01301)', 'Barak', 'None', 'bar-ak\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Hebrew origin («01301»); Barak, an Israelite:--Barak.', 'Barak = \"lightning\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a commander of the Israelites</OL>'),
(914, 'Baracivaß', 'of Hebrew origin (01296)', 'Barachias', 'None', 'bar-akh-ee\'-as', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Hebrew origin («01296»); Barachias (i.e. Berechijah), an Israelite:--Barachias.', 'Barachiah = \"Jehovah blesses\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>said to be the father of the Zachariah slain in the temple</OL>'),
(915, 'bavrbaroß', 'of uncertain derivation', 'barbaros', '1:546,94', 'bar\'-bar-os', 'Adjective', 'of uncertain derivation; a foreigner (i.e. non-Greek):--barbarian(-rous).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>one whose speech is rude, rough and harsh<LI>one who speaks a foreign or strange language which is not understood by another<LI>used by the Greeks of any foreigner ignorant of the Greek language, whether mental or moral, with the added notion after the Persian war, of rudeness and brutality. The word is used in the N.T. without the idea of reproachfulness.</OL>'),
(916, 'barevw', 'from (926)', 'bareo', '1:558,95', 'bar-eh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «926»; to weigh down (figuratively):--burden, charge, heavy, press.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to burden, weigh down, depress</OL>'),
(917, 'barevwß', 'from (926)', 'bareos', 'None', 'bar-eh\'-oce', 'Adverb', 'adverb from «926»; heavily (figuratively):--dull.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>heavily, with difficulty</OL>'),
(918, 'Barqolomai\'oß', 'of Aramaic origin (01247) and (08526)', 'Bartholomaios', 'None', 'bar-thol-om-ah\'-yos', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Chaldee origin (1247 and «08526»); son of Tolmai; Bar-tholomoeus, a Christian apostle:--Bartholomeus.', 'Bartholomew = \"son of Tolmai\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>one of the twelve apostles of Christ</OL>'),
(919, 'Barihsou\'ß', 'of Aramaic origin (01247) and (03091)', 'Bariesous', 'None', 'bar-ee-ay-sooce\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Chaldee origin (1247 and «03091»); son of Jesus (or Joshua); Bar-jesus, an Israelite:--Barjesus.', 'Barjesus = \"son of Jesus\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a certain false prophet</OL>'),
(920, 'Bariwna\'ß', 'of Aramaic origin (01247) and (03124)', 'Barionas', 'None', 'bar-ee-oo-nas\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Chaldee origin (1247 and «03124»); son of Jonas (or Jonah); Bar-jonas, an Israelite:--Bar-jona.', 'Barjona = \"son of Jonah\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the surname of the apostle Peter</OL>'),
(921, 'Barnavbaß', 'of Aramaic origin (01247) and (05029)', 'Barnabas', 'None', 'bar-nab\'-as', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Chaldee origin (1247 and «05029»); son of Nabas (i.e. prophecy); Barnabas, an Israelite:--Barnabas.', 'Barnabas = \"son of rest\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the surname of Joses or Joseph, a Levite, a native of Cyprus He was a distinguished Christian teacher and companion and colleague of Paul.</OL>'),
(922, 'bavroß', 'probably from the same as (939) (through the notion of going down; cf (899))', 'baros', '1:553,95', 'bar\'-os', 'Noun Neuter', 'probably from the same as «939» (through the notion of going down; compare «899»); weight; in the New Testament only, figuratively, a load, abundance, authority:--burden(-some), weight.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>heaviness, weight, burden, trouble</OL>'),
(923, 'Barsabba\'ß', 'of Aramaic origin (01247) and probably (06634)', 'Barsabas', 'None', 'bar-sab-as\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Chaldee origin (1247 and probably «06634»); son of Sabas (or Tsaba); Bar-sabas, the name of two Israelites:--Barsabas.', 'Barsabas = \"son of Sabas\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the surname of a certain Joseph (Acts 1:<LI><LI>the surname of a certain Judas (Acts 15:<LI></OL>'),
(924, 'Bartimai\'oß', 'of Aramaic origin (01247) and (02931)', 'Bartimaios', 'None', 'bar-tim-ah\'-yos', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Chaldee origin (1247 and «02931»); son of Timoeus (or the unclean); Bar-timoeus, an Israelite:--Bartimaeus.', 'Bartimaeus = \"son of Timaeus\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a certain blind man</OL>'),
(925, 'baruvnw', 'from (926)', 'baruno', 'None', 'bar-oo\'-no', 'Verb', 'from «926»; to burden (figuratively):--overcharge.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to weigh down, overcharge</OL>'),
(926, 'baruvß', 'from the same as (922)', 'barus', '1:556,95', 'bar-ooce\'', 'Adjective', 'from the same as «922»; weighty, i.e. (fig) burdensome, grave:--grievous, heavy, weightier.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>heavy in weight<LI>metaph.<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>burdensome<LI>severe, stern<LI>weighty<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>of great moment</OL><LI>violent, cruel, unsparing</OL></OL>'),
(927, 'baruvtimoß', 'from (926) and (5092)', 'barutimos', 'None', 'bar-oo\'-tim-os', 'Adjective', 'from «926» and «5092»; highly valuable:--very precious.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>of weighty, great value, very precious, costly</OL>'),
(928, 'basanivzw', 'from (931)', 'basanizo', '1:561,96', 'bas-an-id\'-zo', 'Verb', 'from «931»; to torture:--pain, toil, torment, toss, vex.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to test (metals) by the touchstone, which is a black siliceous stone used to test the purity of gold or silver by the colour of the streak produced on it by rubbing it with either metal<LI>to question by applying torture<LI>to torture<LI>to vex with grievous pains (of body or mind), to torment<LI>to be harassed, distressed<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of those who at sea are struggling with a head wind</OL></OL>'),
