(2937, 'ktivsiß', 'from (2936)', 'ktisis', '3:1000,481', 'ktis\'-is', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «2936»; original formation (properly, the act; by implication, the thing, literally or figuratively):--building, creation, creature, ordinance.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the act of founding, establishing, building etc<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>the act of creating, creation<LI>creation i.e. thing created<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>of individual things, beings, a creature, a creation 1b</OL><LI>anything created 1b<LI>after a rabbinical usage (by which a man converted from idolatry to Judaism was called) 1b<LI>the sum or aggregate of things created<LI>institution, ordinance</OL></OL>'),
(2938, 'ktivsma', 'from (2936)', 'ktisma', '3:1000,481', 'ktis\'-mah', 'Noun Neuter', 'from «2936»; an original formation (concretely), i.e. product (created thing):--creature.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>thing founded<LI>created thing</OL>'),
(2939, 'ktivsthß', 'from (2936)', 'ktistes', '3:1000,481', 'ktis-tace\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «2936»; a founder, i.e. God (as author of all things):--Creator.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a founder<LI>a creator</OL>'),
(2940, 'kubeiva', 'from kubos (a \"cube\", i.e. die for playing)', 'kubeia', 'None', 'koo-bi\'-ah', 'Noun Feminine', 'from kubos (a \"cube\", i.e. die for playing); gambling, i.e. (figuratively) artifice or fraud:--sleight.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>dice playing<LI>metaph. the deception of men, because dice players sometimes cheated and defrauded their fellow players</OL>'),
(2941, 'kubevrnhsiß', 'from kubernao (of Latin origin, to steer)', 'kubernesis', '3:1035,486', 'koo-ber\'-nay-sis', 'Noun Feminine', 'from kubernao (of Latin origin, to steer); pilotage, i.e. (figuratively) directorship (in the church):--government.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a governing, government</OL>'),
(2942, 'kubernhvthß', 'from the same as (2941)', 'kubernetes', 'None', 'koo-ber-nay\'-tace', 'Noun Masculine', 'from the same as «2941»; helmsman, i.e. (by implication) captain:--(ship) master.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>steersman, helmsman, sailing master</OL>'),
(2943, 'kukleuvw', 'from the same as (2945)', 'kuklothen', 'None', 'koo-kloth\'-en', 'Adverb', 'adverb from the same as «2945»; from the circle, i.e. all around:--(round) about.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>round about, from all sides, all around</OL>'),
(2944, 'kuklovw', 'from the same as (2945)', 'kukloo', 'None', 'koo-klo\'-o', 'Verb', 'from the same as «2945»; to encircle, i.e. surround:--compass (about), come (stand) round about.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to go around, lead around<LI>to surround, encircle, encompass<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of persons standing around<LI>of besiegers</OL></OL>'),
(2945, 'kuvklw/', 'as if dative case of kuklos (a ring, \"cycle\" - akin to (2947))', 'kukloi', 'None', 'koo\'-klo', 'Adverb', 'as if dative case of kuklos (a ring, \"cycle\"; akin to «2947»); i.e. in a circle (by implication, of «1722»), i.e. (adverbially) all around:--round about.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>in a circle, around, round about, on all sides</OL>'),
(2946, 'kulismovß', 'from (2947)', 'kulisma', 'None', 'koo\'-lis-mah', 'Noun Neuter', 'from «2947»; a wallow (the effect of rolling), i.e. filth:--wallowing.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>thing rolled, rolled (wallowed) mud or mire</OL>'),
(2947, 'kulivw', 'from base of (2949) (through the idea of circularity, cf (2945), (1507))', 'kulioo', 'None', 'koo-lee-o\'-o', 'Verb', 'from the base of «2949» (through the idea of circularity; compare «2945», «1507»); to roll about:--wallow.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a rolling, wallowing<LI>to roll itself in mud<LI>to wallowing in the mire</OL>'),
(2948, 'kullovß', 'from the same as (2947)', 'kullos', 'None', 'kool-los\'', 'Adjective', 'from the same as «2947»; rocking about, i.e. crippled (maimed, in feet or hands):--maimed.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>crooked<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of the members of the body<LI>injured, disabled</OL><LI>maimed, mutilated</OL>'),
(2949, 'ku\'ma', 'from kuo (to swell [with young], i.e bend, curve)', 'kuma', 'None', 'koo\'-mah', 'Noun Neuter', 'from kuo (to swell (with young), i.e. bend, curve); a billow (as bursting or toppling):--wave.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a wave (swell) esp. of the sea or of a lake<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of impulse and restless men, tossed to and fro by their raging passions</OL></OL>'),
(2950, 'kuvmbalon', 'from a derivative of the base of (2949)', 'kumbalon', '3:1037,486', 'koom\'-bal-on', 'Noun Neuter', 'from a derivative of the base of «2949»; a \"cymbal\" (as hollow):--cymbal.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a cymbal, i.e. a hollow basin of brass, producing when struck together a musical sound</OL>'),
(2951, 'kuvminon', 'of foreign origin, cf (03646)', 'kuminon', 'None', 'koo\'-min-on', 'Noun Neuter', 'of foreign origin (compare «03646»); dill or fennel (\"cummin\"):--cummin.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>cummin is a cultivated plant in Palestine with seeds that have a bitter warm taste and an aromatic flavour</OL>'),
(2952, 'kunavrion', 'from a presumed derivative of (2965)', 'kunarion', '3:1104,494', 'koo-nar\'-ee-on', 'Noun Neuter', 'neuter of a presumed derivative of «2965»; a puppy:--dog.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a little dog</OL>'),
(2953, 'Kuvprioß', 'from (2954)', 'Kuprios', 'None', 'koo\'-pree-os', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «2954»; a Cyprian (Cypriot), i.e. inhabitant of Cyprus:--of Cyprus.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a Cyprian or Cypriote, i.e. a native of Cyprus</OL>'),
(2954, 'Kuvproß', 'of uncertain origin', 'Kupros', 'None', 'koo\'-pros', 'Noun Location', 'of uncertain origin; Cyprus, an island in the Mediterranean:--Cyprus.', 'Cyprus = \"love: a blossom\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a very fertile and delightful island of the Mediterranean, lying between Cilicia and Syria</OL>'),
(2955, 'kuvptw', 'probably from the base of (2949)', 'kupto', 'None', 'koop\'-to', 'Verb', 'probably from the base of «2949»; to bend forward:--stoop (down).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to stoop down, bend forward, to bow the head</OL>'),
(2956, 'Kurhnai\'oß', 'from (2957)', 'Kurenaios', 'None', 'koo-ray-nah\'-yos', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «2957»; i.e. Cyrenaean, i.e. inhabitant of Cyrene:--of Cyrene, Cyrenian.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a native of Cyrene</OL>'),
(2957, 'Kurhvnh', 'of uncertain derivation', 'Kurene', 'None', 'koo-ray\'-nay', 'Noun Location', 'of uncertain derivation; Cyrene, a region of Africa:--Cyrene.', 'Cyrene = \"supremacy of the bridle\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a large and very flourishing city of Libya Cyrenaica or Pentapolitana, about 11 miles (17 km) from the sea. Among its inhabitants were a great number of Jews, whom Ptolemy I. had brought there, and invested with the right of citizens</OL>'),
(2958, 'Kurhvnioß', 'of Latin origin', 'Kurenios', 'None', 'koo-ray\'-nee-os', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Latin origin; Cyrenius (i.e. Quirinus), a Roman:--Cyrenius.', 'Cyrenius = \"warrior\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the Greek form of the Roman name Quirinus. His full name is Publius Sulpicius Quirinus. He was consul B.C. 12., and was made governor of Syria after the banishment of Archelaus in A.D. 6. He was probably twice governor of Syria; his first governorship extended from B.C. 4 (the year of Christ\'s birth) to B.C. 1. It was during this time that he was sent to make enrolment which caused Joseph and Mary to visit Bethlehem. Luke 2:2. The second enrolment is mentioned in Acts 5:37.</OL>'),
(2959, 'kuriva', 'from (2962)', 'Kuria', '3:1095,486', 'koo-ree\'-ah', 'Noun Feminine', 'feminine of «2962»; Cyria, a Christian woman:--lady.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a Christian woman to whom the second Epistle of John is addressed</OL>'),
(2960, 'kuriakovß', 'from (2962)', 'kuriakos', '3:1095,486', 'koo-ree-ak-os\'', 'Adjective', 'from «2962»; belonging to the Lord (Jehovah or Jesus):--Lord\'s.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>belonging to the Lord<LI>related to the Lord</OL>'),
(2961, 'kurieuvw', 'from (2962)', 'kurieuo', '3:1097,486', 'ko-ree-yoo\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «2962»; to rule:--have dominion over, lord, be lord of, exercise lordship over.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to be lord of, to rule, have dominion over<LI>of things and forces<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to exercise influence upon, to have power over</OL></OL>'),
(2962, 'kuvrioß', 'from kuros (supremacy)', 'kurios', '3:1039,486', 'koo\'-ree-os', 'Noun Masculine', 'from kuros (supremacy); supreme in authority, i.e. (as noun) controller; by implication, Master (as a respectful title):-- God, Lord, master, Sir.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>he to whom a person or thing belongs, about which he has power of deciding; master, lord<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>the possessor and disposer of a thing<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the owner; one who has control of the person, the master<LI>in the state: the sovereign, prince, chief, the Roman emperor</OL><LI>is a title of honour expressive of respect and reverence, with which servants greet their master<LI>this title is given to: God, the Messiah</OL></OL>'),
(2963, 'kuriovthß', 'from (2962)', 'kuriotes', '3:1096,486', 'koo-ree-ot\'-ace', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «2962»; mastery, i.e. (concretely and collectively) rulers:--dominion, government.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>dominion, power, lordship<LI>in the NT: one who possesses dominion</OL>'),
(2964, 'kurovw', 'from the same as (2962)', 'kuroo', '3:1098,486', 'koo-ro\'-o', 'Verb', 'from the same as «2962»; to make authoritative, i.e. ratify:--confirm.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to make valid<LI>to confirm publicly or solemnly, to ratify</OL>'),
(2965, 'kuvwn', 'a root word', 'kuon', '3:1101,', 'koo\'-ohn', 'Noun Masculine', 'a primary word; a dog (\"hound\") (literally or figuratively):--dog.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a dog<LI>metaph. a man of impure mind, an impudent man</OL>'),
(2966, 'kw\'lon', 'from the base of (2849)', 'kolon', 'None', 'ko\'-lon', 'Noun Neuter', 'from the base of «2849»; a limb of the body (as if lopped):--carcase.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a member of a body, particularly the more external and prominent members esp. the feet<LI>a dead body, corpse, inasmuch as the members of a corpse are loose and fall apart</OL>'),
(2967, 'kwluvw', 'from the base of (2849)', 'koluo', 'None', 'ko-loo\'-o', 'Verb', 'from the base of «2849»; to estop, i.e. prevent (by word or act):--forbid, hinder, keep from, let, not suffer, withstand.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to hinder, prevent forbid<LI>to withhold a thing from anyone<LI>to deny or refuse one a thing</OL>'),
(2968, 'kwvmh', 'from (2749)', 'kome', 'None', 'ko\'-may', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «2749»; a hamlet (as if laid down):--town, village.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the common sleeping place to which labourers in the field return, a village<LI>the name of the city near which the villages lie and to whose municipality they belong<LI>the inhabitants of villages</OL>'),
(2969, 'kwmovpoliß', 'from (2968) and (4172)', 'komopolis', 'None', 'ko-mop\'-ol-is', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «2968» and «4172»; an unwalled city:--town.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a village approximating in size and number of inhabitants to a city, a village city, a town</OL>'),
(2970, 'kw\'moß', 'from (2749)', 'komos', 'None', 'ko\'-mos', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «2749»; a carousal (as if letting loose):--revelling, rioting.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a revel, carousal<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>a nocturnal and riotous procession of half drunken and frolicsome fellows who after supper parade through the streets with torches and music in honour of Bacchus or some other deity, and sing and play before houses of male and female friends; hence used generally of feasts and drinking parties that are protracted till late at night and indulge in revelry</OL></OL>'),
(2971, 'kwvnwy', 'apparently a derivative of the base of (2759) and a derivative of (3700)', 'konops', 'None', 'ko\'-nopes', 'Noun Masculine', 'apparently a derivative of the base of «2759» and a derivative of «3700»; a mosquito (from its stinging proboscis):--gnat.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a wine gnat or midge that is bred in fermenting and evaporating wine</OL>'),
(2972, 'Kw\'ß', 'of uncertain origin', 'Kos', 'None', 'koce', 'Noun Location', 'of uncertain origin; Cos, an island in the Mediterranean:--Cos.', 'Coos = \"a public prison\"'),
(2973, 'Kwsavm', 'of Hebrew origin cf (07081)', 'Kosam', 'None', 'ko-sam\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Hebrew origin (compare «07081»); Cosam (i.e. Kosam) an Israelite:--Cosam.', 'Cosam = \"divining\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>ancestor of Christ\'s</OL>'),
(2974, 'kwfovß', 'from (2875)', 'kophos', 'None', 'ko-fos\'', 'Adjective', 'from «2875»; blunted, i.e. (figuratively) of hearing (deaf) or speech (dumb):--deaf, dumb, speechless.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>blunted, dull<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>blunted (or lamed) in tongue, dumb<LI>blunted, dull in hearing<LI>deaf</OL></OL>'),
(2975, 'lagcavnw', 'a prolonged form of a primary verb, which is only used as an alternate in certain tenses', 'lagchano', '4:1,495', 'lang-khan\'-o', 'Verb', 'a prolonged form of a primary verb, which is only used as an alternate in certain tenses; to lot, i.e. determine (by implication, receive) especially by lot:--his lot be, cast lots, obtain.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to obtain by lot<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to receive by divine allotment, obtain</OL><LI>to cast lots, determine by lot</OL>'),
(2976, 'Lavzaroß', 'probably of Hebrew origin (0499)', 'Lazaros', 'None', 'lad\'-zar-os', 'Noun Masculine', 'probably of Hebrew origin («0499»); Lazarus (i.e. Elazar), the name of two Israelites (one imaginary):--Lazarus.', 'Lazarus = \"whom God helps\" (a form of the Hebrew name Eleazar)<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>an inhabitant of Bethany, beloved by Christ and raised from the dead by him<LI>a very poor and wretched person to whom Jesus referred to in Luke 16:20-25</OL>'),
(2977, 'lavqra/', 'from (2990)', 'lathra', 'None', 'lath\'-rah', 'Adverb', 'adverb from «2990»; privately:--privily, secretly.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>secretly</OL>'),
(2978, 'lai\'lay', 'of uncertain derivation', 'lailaps', 'None', 'lah\'-ee-laps', 'Noun Feminine', 'of uncertain derivation; a whirlwind (squall):--storm, tempest.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a whirlwind, a tempestuous wind<LI>a violent attack of wind, a squall<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>never a single gust nor a steady blowing wind, however violent, but a storm breaking forth from black thunder clouds in furious gusts, with floods of rain, and throwing everything topsy-turvy</OL></OL>'),
(2979, 'lakavw', 'from adverb lax (heelwise)', 'laktizo', '4:3,495', 'lak-tid\'-zo', 'Verb', 'from adverb lax (heelwise); to recalcitrate:--kick.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to kick, strike with the heel</OL>'),
(2980, 'lalevw', 'a prolonged form of an otherwise obsolete verb', 'laleo', '4:69,505', 'lal-eh\'-o', 'Verb', 'a prolonged form of an otherwise obsolete verb; to talk, i.e. utter words:--preach, say, speak (after), talk, tell, utter. Compare «3004».', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to utter a voice or emit a sound<LI>to speak<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to use the tongue or the faculty of speech<LI>to utter articulate sounds</OL><LI>to talk<LI>to utter, tell<LI>to use words in order to declare one\'s mind and disclose one\'s thoughts<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to speak</OL></OL>'),
(2981, 'laliav', 'from (2980)', 'lalia', 'None', 'lal-ee-ah\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «2980»; talk:--saying, speech.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>speech, i.e a story<LI>dialect, mode of speech, pronunciation<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>speech which discloses the speaker\'s native country</OL></OL>'),
(2982, 'lamav', 'transliterated from Aramaic', 'lama', 'None', 'lam-ah\'', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>why</OL>', 'or lamma lam-mah\'; of Hebrew origin (4100 with prepositional prefix); lama (i.e. why):--lama.', ''),
(2983, 'lambavnw', 'a prolonged form of a primary verb, which is use only as an alternate in certain tenses', 'lambano', '4:5,495', 'lam-ban\'-o', 'Verb', 'a prolonged form of a primary verb, which is use only as an alternate in certain tenses; to take (in very many applications, literally and figuratively (properly objective or active, to get hold of; whereas «1209» is rather subjective or passive, to have offered to one; while «138» is more violent, to seize or remove)):--accept, + be amazed, assay, attain, bring, × when I call, catch, come on (X unto), + forget, have, hold, obtain, receive (X after), take (away, up).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to take<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to take with the hand, lay hold of, any person or thing in order to use it<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to take up a thing to be carried<LI>to take upon one\'s self</OL><LI>to take in order to carry away<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>without the notion of violence, i,e to remove, take away</OL><LI>to take what is one\'s own, to take to one\'s self, to make one\'s own<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to claim, procure, for one\'s self 1c</OL><LI>to associate with one\'s self as companion, attendant<OL TYPE=\"2\"><LI>of that which when taken is not let go, to seize, to lay hold of, apprehend<LI>to take by craft (our catch, used of hunters, fisherman, etc.), to circumvent one by fraud<LI>to take to one\'s self, lay hold upon, take possession of, i.e. to appropriate to one\'s self<LI>catch at, reach after, strive to obtain<LI>to take a thing due, to collect, gather (tribute)</OL><LI>to take<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to admit, receive<LI>to receive what is offered<LI>not to refuse or reject<LI>to receive a person, give him access to one\'s self, 1d</OL></OL><LI>to regard any one\'s power, rank, external circumstances, and on that account to do some injustice or neglect something<OL TYPE=\"e\"><LI>to take, to choose, select<LI>to take beginning, to prove anything, to make a trial of, to experience</OL><LI>to receive (what is given), to gain, get, obtain, to get back</OL>'),
(2984, 'Lavmec', 'of Hebrew origin (03929)', 'Lamech', 'None', 'lam\'-ekh', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Hebrew origin («03929»); Lamech (i.e. Lemek), a patriarch:--Lamech.', 'Lamech = \"why thus with thee?: unto bringing low\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the father of Noah</OL>'),
(2985, 'lampavß', 'from (2989)', 'lampas', '4:16,497', 'lam-pas\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «2989»; a \"lamp\" or flambeau:--lamp, light, torch.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a torch<LI>a lamp, the flame of which is fed with oil</OL>'),
(2986, 'lamprovß', 'from the same as (2985)', 'lampros', '4:16,497', 'lam-pros\'', 'Adjective', 'from the same as «2985»; radiant; by analogy, limpid; figuratively, magnificent or sumptuous (in appearance):--bright, clear, gay, goodly, gorgeous, white.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>shining<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>brilliant<LI>clear, transparent</OL><LI>splendid, magnificent<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>splendid things i.e. luxuries or elegancies in dress or style</OL></OL>'),
(2987, 'lamprovthß', 'from (2986)', 'lamprotes', 'None', 'lam-prot\'-ace', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «2986»; brilliancy:--brightness.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>brightness, brilliancy</OL>'),
(2988, 'lamprw\'ß', 'from (2986)', 'lampros', 'None', 'lam-proce\'', 'Adverb', 'adverb from «2986»; brilliantly, i.e. figuratively, luxuriously:--sumptuously.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>splendidly, magnificently<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of sumptuous living</OL></OL>'),
(2989, 'lavmpw', 'a primary verb', 'lampo', '4:16,497', 'lam\'-po', 'Verb', 'a primary verb; to beam, i.e. radiate brilliancy (literally or figuratively):--give light, shine.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to shine</OL>'),
(2990, 'lanqavnw', 'a prolonged form of a primitive verb, which is used only as an alt. in certain tenses', 'lanthano', 'None', 'lan-than\'-o', 'Verb', 'a prolonged form of a primary verb, which is used only as an alternate in certain tenses; to lie hid (literally or figuratively); often used adverbially, unwittingly:--be hid, be ignorant of, unawares.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to be hidden, to be hidden from one, secretly, unawares, without knowing</OL>'),
(2991, 'laxeutovß', 'from a compound of las (a stone) and the base of (3584) (in its original sense of scraping)', 'laxeutos', 'None', 'lax-yoo-tos\'', 'Adjective', 'from a compound of las (a stone) and the base of «3584» (in its original sense of scraping); rock-quarried:--hewn in stone.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>cut out of stone</OL>'),
(2992, 'laovß', 'apparently a primary word', 'laos', '4:29,499', 'lah-os\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'apparently a primary word; a people (in general; thus differing from «1218», which denotes one\'s own populace):--people.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a people, people group, tribe, nation, all those who are of the same stock and language<LI>of a great part of the population gathered together anywhere</OL>'),
(2993, 'Laodivkeia', 'from a compound of (2992) and (1349)', 'Laodikeia', 'None', 'lah-od-ik\'-i-ah', 'Noun Location', 'from a compound of «2992» and «1349»; Laodicia, a place in Asia Minor:--Laodicea.', 'Laodicea = \"justice of the people\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a city of Phrygia, situated on the river Lycus not far from Colosse. It was destroyed by an earthquake in 66 A.D. and rebuilt by Marcus Aurelius. It was the seat of the Christian church.</OL>'),
(2994, 'Laodikeuvß', 'from (2993)', 'Laodikeus', 'None', 'lah-od-ik-yooce\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «2993»; a Laodicean, i.e. inhabitant of Laodicia:--Laodicean.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a Laodicean, an inhabitant of Laodicea</OL>'),
(2995, 'lavrugx', 'of uncertain derivation', 'larugx', '4:57,503', 'lar\'-oongks', 'Noun Masculine', 'of uncertain derivation; the throat (\"larynx\"):--throat.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the throat<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of the instrument or organ of speech</OL></OL>'),
(2996, 'Lasaiva', 'of uncertain origin', 'Lasaia', 'None', 'las-ah\'-yah', 'Noun Location', 'of uncertain origin; Lasaea, a place in Crete:--Lasea.', 'Lasea = \"shaggy\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a city in Crete on the coast near Fair Havens</OL>'),
(2997, 'lavskw', 'a strengthened form of a primary verb, which only occurs in this and another prolonged form as alternate in certain tenses', 'lascho', 'None', 'las\'-kho', 'Verb', 'a strengthened form of a primary verb, which only occurs in this and another prolonged form as alternate in certain tenses; to crack open (from a fall):--burst asunder.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to crack, crackle, crash<LI>to burst asunder with a crack, crack open</OL>'),
(2998, 'latomevw', 'from the same as the first part of (2991) and the base of (5114)', 'latomeo', 'None', 'lat-om-eh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from the same as the first part of «2991» and the base of «5114»; to quarry:--hew.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to cut stones, to hew out stones</OL>'),
(2999, 'latreiva', 'from (3000)', 'latreia', '4:58,503', 'lat-ri\'-ah', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «3000»; ministration of God, i.e. worship:--(divine) service.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>service rendered for hire<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>any service or ministration: the service of God</OL><LI>the service and worship of God according to the requirements of the Levitical law<LI>to perform sacred services</OL>'),
(3000, 'latreuvw', 'from latris (a hired menial)', 'latreuo', '4:58,503', 'lat-ryoo\'-o', 'Verb', 'from latris (a hired menial); to minister (to God), i.e. render religious homage:--serve, do the service, worship(-per).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to serve for hire<LI>to serve, minister to, either to the gods or men and used alike of slaves and freemen<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>in the NT, to render religious service or homage, to worship<LI>to perform sacred services, to offer gifts, to worship God in the observance of the rites instituted for his worship<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>of priests, to officiate, to discharge the sacred office</OL></OL></OL>'),
(3001, 'lavcanon', 'from lachaino (to dig)', 'lachanon', '4:65,504', 'lakh\'-an-on', 'Noun Neuter', 'from lachaino (to dig); a vegetable:--herb.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>any pot herb, vegetables</OL>'),
(3002, 'Lebbai\'oß', 'of uncertain origin', 'Lebbaios', 'None', 'leb-bah\'-yos', 'Noun Masculine', 'of uncertain origin; Lebbaeus, a Christian:--Lebbaeus.', 'Lebbaeus = \"a man of heart\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>one name of Jude, who was one of the twelve apostles</OL>'),
(3003, 'legiwvn', 'of Latin origin', 'legeon', '4:68,505', 'leg-eh-ohn\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'of Latin origin; a \"legion\", i.e. Roman regiment (figuratively):--legion.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a legion, a body of soldiers whose number differed at different times, and in the time of Augustus seems to have consisted of 6826 men (i.e. 6100 foot soldiers, and 726 horsemen)</OL>'),
(3004, 'levgw', 'a root word', 'lego', '4:69,505', 'leg\'-o', 'Verb', 'a primary verb; properly, to \"lay\" forth, i.e. (figuratively) relate (in words (usually of systematic or set discourse; whereas «2036» and «5346» generally refer to an individual expression or speech respectively; while «4483» is properly to break silence merely, and «2980» means an extended or random harangue)); by implication, to mean:--ask, bid, boast, call, describe, give out, name, put forth, say(-ing, on), shew, speak, tell, utter.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to say, to speak<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>affirm over, maintain<LI>to teach<LI>to exhort, advise, to command, direct<LI>to point out with words, intend, mean, mean to say<LI>to call by name, to call, name<LI>to speak out, speak of, mention</OL></OL>'),
(3005, 'lei\'mma', 'from (3007)', 'leimma', '4:194,523', 'lime\'-mah', 'Noun Neuter', 'from «3007»; a remainder:--remnant.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a remnant</OL>'),
(3006, 'lei\'oß', 'apparently a primary word', 'leios', '4:193,523', 'li\'-os', 'Adjective', 'apparently a primary word; smooth, i.e. \"level\":--smooth.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>smooth, level</OL>'),
(3007, 'leivpw', 'a root word', 'leipo', 'None', 'li\'-po', 'Verb', 'a primary verb; to leave, i.e. (intransitively or passively) to fail or be absent:--be destitute (wanting), lack.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to leave, leave behind, forsake, to be left behind<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to lag, be inferior<LI>to be destitute of, to lack</OL><LI>to be wanting, to fail</OL>'),
(3008, 'leitourgevw', 'from (3011)', 'leitourgeo', '4:215,526', 'li-toorg-eh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «3011»; to be a public servant, i.e. (by analogy) to perform religious or charitable functions (worship, obey, relieve):--minister.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to serve the state at one\'s own cost<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to assume an office which must be administered at one\'s own expense<LI>to discharge a public office at one\'s own cost<LI>to render public service to the state</OL><LI>to do a service, perform a work<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of priests and Levites who were busied with the sacred rites in the tabernacle or the temple<LI>of Christians serving Christ, whether by prayer, or by instructing others concerning the way of salvation, or in some other way<LI>of those who aid others with their resources, and relieve their poverty</OL></OL>'),
(3009, 'leitourgiva', 'from (3008)', 'leitourgia', '4:215,526', 'li-toorg-ee\'-ah', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «3008»; public function (as priest (\"liturgy\") or almsgiver):--ministration(-try), service.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a public office which a citizen undertakes to administer at his own expense<LI>any service<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of military service<LI>of the service of workmen<LI>of that done to nature in the cohabitation of man and wife</OL><LI>biblical usage<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>a service or ministry of the priests relative to the prayers and sacrifices offered to God<LI>a gift or benefaction for the relief of the needy</OL></OL>'),
(3010, 'leitourgikovß', 'from the same as (3008)', 'leitourgikos', '4:231,526', 'li-toorg-ik-os\'', 'Adjective', 'from the same as «3008»; functional publicly (\"liturgic\"); i.e. beneficient:--ministering.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>relating to the performance of service, employed in ministering</OL>'),
(3011, 'leitourgovß', 'from a derivative of (2992) and (2041)', 'leitourgos', '4:229,526', 'li-toorg-os\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'from a derivative of «2992» and «2041»; a public servant, i.e. a functionary in the Temple or Gospel, or (genitive case) a worshipper (of God) or benefactor (of man):--minister(-ed).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a public minister, a servant of the state<LI>a minister, servant<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>so of military labourers<LI>of the temple<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>of one busied with holy things<LI>of a priest</OL><LI>of the servants of a king</OL></OL>'),
(3012, 'levntion', 'of Latin origin', 'lention', 'None', 'len\'-tee-on', 'Noun Neuter', 'of Latin origin; a \"linen\" cloth, i.e. apron:--towel.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a linen cloth, towel<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of the towel or apron with which servants put on when about to work</OL></OL>'),
(3013, 'lepivß', 'from lepo (to peel)', 'lepis', '4:232,529', 'lep-is\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'from lepo (to peel); a flake:--scale.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a scale</OL>'),
(3014, 'levpra', 'from the same as (3013)', 'lepra', '4:233,529', 'lep\'-rah', 'Noun Feminine', 'from the same as «3013»; scaliness, i.e. \"leprosy\":--leprosy.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>leprosy<LI>a most offensive, annoying, dangerous, cutaneous disease, the virus of which generally pervades the whole body, common in Egypt and the East</OL>'),
(3015, 'leprovß', 'from the same as (3014)', 'lepros', '4:233,529', 'lep-ros\'', 'Adjective', 'from the same as «3014»; scaly, i.e. leprous (a leper):--leper.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>scaly, rough<LI>leprous, affected with leprosy</OL>'),
(3016, 'leptovß', 'neuter of a derivative of the same as (3013)', 'lepton', '4:233,*', 'lep-ton\'', 'Adjective', 'neuter of a derivative of the same as «3013»; something scaled (light), i.e. a small coin:--mite.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>thin, small<LI>a small brass coin, equivalent to the eighth part of an \"as\", worth about a 1/5 of a cent</OL>'),
(3017, 'Leuiv', 'of Hebrew origin (03878)', 'Leui', '4:234,529', 'lyoo\'-ee', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Hebrew origin («03878»); Levi, the name of three Israelites:--Levi. Compare «3018».', 'Levi = \"joined\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the third son of the patriarch Jacob by his wife Leah, the founder of the tribe of Israelites which bears his name<LI>the son of Melchi, one of Christ\'s ancestors<LI>the son of Simeon, an ancestor of Christ</OL>'),
(3018, 'Leuivß', 'a form of (3017)', 'Leuis', '4:234,529', 'lyoo-is\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'a form of «3017»; Lewis (i.e. Levi), a Christian:--Levi.', 'Levi = \"joined\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the son of Alphaeus, a collector of customs</OL>'),
(3019, 'Leuivthß', 'from (3017)', 'Leuites', '4:239,530', 'lyoo-ee\'-tace', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «3017»; a Levite, i.e. descendant of Levi:--Levite.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>one of the tribe of Levi<LI>in a narrower sense those were called Levites who, not being of the family of Aaron, for whom alone the priesthood was reserved, served as assistants to the priests. It was their duty to keep the sacred utensils and the temple clean, to provide the sacred loaves, to open and shut the gates of the temple, to sing the sacred hymns in the temple, and to do many other things.</OL>'),
(3020, 'Leuitikovß', 'from (3019)', 'Leuitikos', 'None', 'lyoo-it\'-ee-kos', 'Adjective', 'from «3019»; Levitic, i.e. relating to the Levites:--Levitical.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>Levitical, pertaining to the Levites</OL>'),
(3021, 'leukaivnw', 'from (3022)', 'leukaino', '4:241,530', 'lyoo-kah\'-ee-no', 'Verb', 'from «3022»; to whiten:--make white, whiten.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to whiten, make white</OL>'),
(3022, 'leukovß', 'from luke (\"light\")', 'leukos', '4:241,530', 'lyoo-kos\'', 'Adjective', 'from luke (\"light\"); white:--white.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>light, bright, brilliant<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>brilliant from whiteness, (dazzling) white<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>of the garments of angels, and of those exalted to the splendour of the heavenly state<LI>shining or white garments worn on festive or state occasions<LI>of white garments as the sign of innocence and purity of the soul</OL><LI>dead white<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>of the whitening colour of ripening grain</OL></OL></OL>'),
(3023, 'levwn', 'a root word', 'leon', '4:251,531', 'leh-ohn\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'a primary word; a \"lion\":--lion.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a lion<LI>a brave and mighty hero</OL>Both Christ and Satan are referred to as a lion, indicatinggreat strength, Satan as a \"roaring lion\" (1 Pe. 5:<LI>andChrist as \"the Lion of the tribe of Judah\" (Re. 5:<LI>'),
(3024, 'lhvqh', 'from (2990)', 'lethe', 'None', 'lay\'-thay', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «2990»; forgetfulness:--+ forget.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>forgetfulness</OL>'),
(3025, 'lh\'myiß', 'apparently a primary word', 'lenos', '4:254,531', 'lay-nos\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'apparently a primary word; a trough, i.e. wine-vat:--winepress.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a tub or trough shaped receptacle, vat, in which grapes are trodden<LI>the lower vat, dug in the ground, into which the must or new wine flowed from the press</OL>'),
(3026, 'lh\'roß', 'apparently a root word', 'leros', 'None', 'lay\'-ros', 'Noun Masculine', 'apparently a primary word; twaddle, i.e. an incredible story:--idle tale.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>idle talk, nonsense</OL>'),
(3027, 'lh/sthvß', 'from leizomai (to plunder)', 'leistes', '4:257,532', 'lace-tace\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'from leizomai (to plunder); a brigand:--robber, thief.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a robber, plunderer, freebooter, brigand</OL>'),
(3028, 'lh\'yiß', 'from (2983)', 'lepsis', 'None', 'lape\'-sis', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «2983»; receipt (the act):--receiving.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a receiving</OL>'),
(3029, 'livan', 'of uncertain affinity', 'lian', 'None', 'lee\'-an', 'Adverb', 'of uncertain affinity; much (adverbially):--exceeding, great(-ly), sore, very (+ chiefest).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>greatly, exceedingly, exceedingly beyond measure</OL>'),
(3030, 'livbanoß', 'of foreign origin (03828)', 'libanos', '4:263,533', 'lib\'-an-os', 'Noun Masculine', 'of foreign origin («03828»); the incense-tree, i.e. (by implication) incense itself:--frankincense.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the frankincense tree<LI>the perfume, frankincense</OL>'),
(3031, 'libanwtovß', 'from (3030)', 'libanotos', '4:263,533', 'lib-an-o-tos\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «3030»; frankincense, i.e. (by extension) a censer for burning it:--censer.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the gum exuding from a frankincense tree<LI>a censer</OL>'),
(3032, 'Liberti\'noß', 'of Latin origin', 'Libertinos', '4:265,533', 'lib-er-tee\'-nos', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Latin origin; a Roman freedman:--Libertine.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>one who has been liberated from slavery, a freedman, or the son of a freed man<LI>Libertine, denotes Jews (according to Philo) who had been made captives of the Romans under Pompey but were afterwards set free; and who although they had fixed their abode in Rome, had built at their own expense a synagogue at Jerusalem which they frequented when in that city, The name Libertines adhered to them to distinguish them from free born Jews who had subsequently taken up their residence at Rome. Evidence seems to have been discovered of the existence of a \"synagogue of the Libertines\" at Pompeii.</OL>'),
(3033, 'Libuvh', 'probably from (3047)', 'Libue', 'None', 'lib-oo\'-ay', 'Noun Location', 'probably from «3047»; Libye, a region of Africa:--Libya.', 'Libya = \"afflicted or weeping\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a large region of northern Africa, bordering Egypt. In that portion of it which had Cyrene for its capital and was thence called Libya Cyrenaica.</OL>'),
(3034, 'liqavzw', 'from (3037)', 'lithazo', '4:267,533', 'lith-ad\'-zo', 'Verb', 'from «3037»; to lapidate:--stone.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to overwhelm or pelt with stones<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of stoning, a Jewish mode of punishment</OL><LI>to pelt one with stones, in order either to wound or kill him</OL>'),
(3035, 'livqinoß', 'from (3037)', 'lithinos', '4:268,534', 'lith-ee\'-nos', 'Adjective', 'from «3037»; stony, i.e. made of stone:--of stone.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>of stone</OL>'),
(3036, 'liqobolevw', 'from a compound of (3037) and (906)', 'lithoboleo', '4:267,533', 'lith-ob-ol-eh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from a compound of «3037» and «906»; to throw stones, i.e. lapidate:--stone, cast stones.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to kill by stoning, to stone<LI>to pelt one with stones</OL>'),
(3037, 'livqoß', 'apparently a primary word', 'lithos', '4:268,534', 'lee\'-thos', 'Noun Masculine', 'apparently a primary word; a stone (literally or figuratively):--(mill-, stumbling-)stone.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a stone<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of small stones<LI>of building stones<LI>metaph. of Christ</OL></OL>'),
(3038, 'liqovstrwtoß', 'from (3037) and a derivative of (4766)', 'lithostrotos', 'None', 'lith-os\'-tro-tos', 'Adjective', 'from «3037» and a derivative of «4766»; stone-strewed, i.e. a tessellated mosaic on which the Roman tribunal was placed:--Pavement.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>spread (paved with stones)<LI>a mosaic or tessellated pavement<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of a place near the praetorium or palace of Jerusalem<LI>an apartment whose pavement consists of tessellated work<LI>of places in the outer courts of temple</OL></OL>The word for \"Pavement\" is found nowhere else in the NT, but itsHebrew equivalent occurs just once in the OT, and it is evident thatthe Holy Sprit would have us link the two passages together. In 2Kings 16:17 we read, \"King Ahaz cut off the borders of the bases, andremoved the laver from off them; and took down the sea from off thebrazen oxen that were under it and put it upon a \"pavement\" ofstones.\" In Ahaz\'s case, his act was the conclusive token of hissurrender to abject apostasy. So here of Pilate coming down to thelevel of the apostate Jews. In the former case it was a Jewish rulerdominated by a Gentile idolater; in the latter, a Gentile idolater,dominated by Jews who rejected their Messiah! AWP');
INSERT INTO `greek_lexicon` (`number`, `orig_word`, `word_orig`, `translit`, `tdnt`, `phonetic`, `part_of_speech`, `st_def`, `IPD_def`) VALUES
(3039, 'likmavw', 'from likmos, the equivalent of liknon (a winnowing fan or basket)', 'likmao', '4:280,535', 'lik-mah\'-o', 'Verb', 'from likmos, the equivalent of liknon (a winnowing fan or basket); to winnow, i.e. (by analogy), to triturate:--grind to powder.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to winnow, cleanse away the chaff from the grain by winnowing<LI>to scatter<LI>to crush to pieces, grind to powder</OL>'),
(3040, 'limhvn', 'apparently a root word', 'limen', 'None', 'lee-mane\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'apparently a primary word; a harbor:--haven. Compare «2568».', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a harbour, haven</OL>'),
(3041, 'livmnh', 'probably from (3040) (through the idea of nearness of shore)', 'limne', 'None', 'lim\'-nay', 'Noun Feminine', 'probably from «3040» (through the idea of nearness of shore); a pond (large or small):--lake.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a lake</OL>'),
(3042, 'limovß', 'probably from (3007) (through the idea of destitution)', 'limos', '6:12,820', 'lee-mos\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'probably from «3007» (through the idea of destitution); a scarcity of food:--dearth, famine, hunger.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>scarcity of harvest, famine</OL>'),
(3043, 'livnon', 'probably a root word', 'linon', 'None', 'lee\'-non', 'Noun Neuter', 'probably a primary word; flax, i.e. (by implication) \"linen\":--linen.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>linen clothing made from flax</OL>'),
(3044, 'Livnoß', 'perhaps from (3043)', 'Linos', 'None', 'lee\'-nos', 'Noun Masculine', 'perhaps from «3043»; Linus, a Christian:--Linus.', 'Linus = \"a net\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a Christian at Rome, known to Paul and to Timothy, 2 Ti. 4:21, who was the first bishop of Rome after the apostles (A.D.<LI></OL>'),
(3045, 'liparovß', 'from lipos (grease)', 'liparos', 'None', 'lip-ar-os\'', 'Adjective', 'from lipos (grease); fat, i.e. (figuratively) sumptuous:--dainty.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>things which pertain to a sumptuous and delicate style of living</OL>'),
(3046, 'livtra', 'of Latin origin [libra]', 'litra', 'None', 'lee\'-trah', 'Noun Feminine', 'of Latin origin (libra); a pound in weight:--pound.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a pound, a weight of 12 ounces (340 gm)</OL>'),
(3047, 'livy', 'probably from leibo (to pour a \"libation\")', 'lips', 'None', 'leeps', 'Noun Masculine', 'probably from leibo (to pour a \"libation\"); the south(- west) wind (as bringing rain, i.e. (by extension) the south quarter):--southwest.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the south west wind<LI>the quarter of the heavens whence the south west wind blows</OL>'),
(3048, 'logeiva', 'from (3056) (in the commercial sense)', 'logia', '4:282,*', 'log-ee\'-ah', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «3056» (in the commercial sense); a contribution:--collection, gathering.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a collection<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of money gathered for the relief of the poor</OL></OL>'),
(3049, 'logivzomai', 'middle voice from (3056)', 'logizomai', '4:284,536', 'log-id\'-zom-ahee', 'Verb', 'middle voice from «3056»; to take an inventory, i.e. estimate (literally or figuratively):--conclude, (ac-)count (of), + despise, esteem, impute, lay, number, reason, reckon, suppose, think (on).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to reckon, count, compute, calculate, count over<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to take into account, to make an account of<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>metaph. to pass to one\'s account, to impute<LI>a thing is reckoned as or to be something, i.e. as availing for or equivalent to something, as having the like force and weight</OL><LI>to number among, reckon with<LI>to reckon or account</OL><LI>to reckon inward, count up or weigh the reasons, to deliberate<LI>by reckoning up all the reasons, to gather or infer<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to consider, take into account, weigh, meditate on<LI>to suppose, deem, judge<LI>to determine, purpose, decide</OL></OL>This word deals with reality. If I \"logizomai\" or reckon that my bank book has $25 in it, it has $25 in it. Otherwise I am deceiving myself. This word refers to facts not suppositions.'),
(3050, 'logikovß', 'from (3056)', 'logikos', '4:142,505', 'log-ik-os\'', 'Adjective', 'from «3056»; rational (\"logical\"):--reasonable, of the word.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>pertaining to speech or speaking<LI>pertaining to the reason or logic<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>spiritual, pertaining to the soul<LI>agreeable to reason, following reason, reasonable, logical</OL></OL>'),
(3051, 'lovgion', 'from (3052)', 'logion', '4:137,505', 'log\'-ee-on', 'Noun Neuter', 'neuter of «3052»; an utterance (of God):--oracle.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a brief utterance, a divine oracle (doubtless because oracles were generally brief)<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>in the NT, the words or utterances of God<LI>of the contents of the Mosaic law</OL></OL>'),
(3052, 'lovgioß', 'from (3056)', 'logios', '4:136,505', 'log\'-ee-os', 'Adjective', 'from «3056»; fluent, i.e. an orator:--eloquent.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>learned, a man of letters, skilled in literature and the arts, esp. versed in history and the antiquities<LI>skilled in speech, eloquent<LI>rational, wise</OL>'),
(3053, 'logismovß', 'from (3049)', 'logismos', '4:284,536', 'log-is-mos\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «3049»; computation, i.e. (figuratively) reasoning (conscience, conceit):--imagination, thought.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a reckoning, computation<LI>a reasoning: such as is hostile to the Christian faith<LI>a judgment, decision: such as conscience passes</OL>'),
(3054, 'logomacevw', 'from a compound of (3056) and (3164)', 'logomacheo', '4:143,505', 'log-om-akh-eh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from a compound of «3056» and «3164»; to be disputatious (on trifles):--strive about words.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to contend about words<LI>to wrangle about empty and trifling matters</OL>'),
(3055, 'logomaciva', 'from the same as (3054)', 'logomachia', '4:143,505', 'log-om-akh-ee\'-ah', 'Noun Feminine', 'from the same as «3054»; disputation about trifles (\"logomachy\"):--strife of words.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to contend about words<LI>to wrangle about empty and trifling matters</OL>'),
(3056, 'lovgoß', 'from (3004)', 'logos', '4:69,505', 'log\'-os', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «3004»; something said (including the thought); by implication, a topic (subject of discourse), also reasoning (the mental faculty) or motive; by extension, a computation; specially, (with the article in John) the Divine Expression (i.e. Christ):--account, cause, communication, × concerning, doctrine, fame, × have to do, intent, matter, mouth, preaching, question, reason, + reckon, remove, say(-ing), shew, × speaker, speech, talk, thing, + none of these things move me, tidings, treatise, utterance, word, work.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>of speech<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>a word, uttered by a living voice, embodies a conception or idea<LI>what someone has said<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a word<LI>the sayings of God<LI>decree, mandate or order<LI>of the moral precepts given by God<LI>Old Testament prophecy given by the prophets<LI>what is declared, a thought, declaration, aphorism, a weighty saying, a dictum, a maxim</OL><LI>discourse<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the act of speaking, speech<LI>the faculty of speech, skill and practice in speaking<LI>a kind or style of speaking<LI>a continuous speaking discourse - instruction</OL><LI>doctrine, teaching<LI>anything reported in speech; a narration, narrative<LI>matter under discussion, thing spoken of, affair, a matter in dispute, case, suit at law<LI>the thing spoken of or talked about; event, deed</OL><LI>its use as respect to the MIND alone<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>reason, the mental faculty of thinking, meditating, reasoning, calculating<LI>account, i.e. regard, consideration<LI>account, i.e. reckoning, score<LI>account, i.e. answer or explanation in reference to judgment<LI>relation, i.e. with whom as judge we stand in relation<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>reason would</OL><LI>reason, cause, ground</OL><LI>In John, denotes the essential Word of God, Jesus Christ, the personal wisdom and power in union with God, his minister in creation and government of the universe, the cause of all the world\'s life both physical and ethical, which for the procurement of man\'s salvation put on human nature in the person of Jesus the Messiah, the second person in the Godhead, and shone forth conspicuously from His words and deeds.</OL>A Greek philosopher named Heraclitus first used the term Logos around600 B.C. to designate the divine reason or plan which coordinates achanging universe. This word was well suited to John\'s purpose inJohn 1.'),
