(4596, 'shrikovß', 'from Ser (an Indian tribe from whom silk was procured, hence the name of the silk-worm)', 'serikos', 'None', 'say-ree-kos\'', 'Adjective', 'from Ser (an Indian tribe from whom silk was procured; hence the name of the silk-worm); Seric, i.e. silken (neuter as noun, a silky fabric):--silk.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>made of silk<LI>silk, i.e. the fabric, silken garments</OL>'),
(4597, 'shvß', 'apparently of Hebrew origin (05580)', 'ses', '7:275,1025', 'sace', 'Noun Neuter', 'apparently of Hebrew origin («05580»); a moth:--moth.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a moth, the clothes moth</OL>'),
(4598, 'shtovbrwtoß', 'from (4597) and a derivative of (977)', 'setobrotos', '7:275,1025', 'say-tob\'-ro-tos', 'Adjective', 'from «4597» and a derivative of «977»; moth-eaten:--motheaten.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>moth eaten</OL>'),
(4599, 'sqenovw', 'from sthenos (bodily vigour, probably akin to the base of (2476))', 'sthenoo', 'None', 'sthen-o\'-o', 'Verb', 'from sthenos (bodily vigor; probably akin to the base of «2476»); to strengthen, i.e. (figuratively) confirm (in spiritual knowledge and power):--strengthen.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to make strong, strengthen<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of one\'s soul</OL></OL>'),
(4600, 'siagwvn', 'of uncertain derivation', 'siagon', 'None', 'see-ag-one\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'of uncertain derivation; the jaw-bone, i.e. (by implication) the cheek or side of the face:--cheek.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the jaw, the jaw bone</OL>'),
(4601, 'sigavw', 'from (4602)', 'sigao', 'None', 'see-gah\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4602»; to keep silent (transitively or intransitively):--keep close (secret, silence), hold peace.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to keep silence, hold one\'s peace<LI>to be kept in silence, be concealed</OL>'),
(4602, 'sighv', 'appr. from sizo (to hiss, i.e. hist or hush)', 'sige', 'None', 'see-gay\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'apparently from sizo (to hiss, i.e. hist or hush); silence:--silence. Compare «4623».', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>silence</OL>'),
(4603, 'sivdhroß', 'from (4604)', 'sidereos', 'None', 'sid-ay\'-reh-os', 'Adjective', 'from «4604»; made of iron:--(of) iron.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>made of iron</OL>'),
(4604, 'sidhrou\'ß', 'of uncertain derivation', 'sideros', 'None', 'sid\'-ay-ros', 'Noun Masculine', 'of uncertain derivation; iron:--iron.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>iron</OL>'),
(4605, 'Sidwvn', 'of Hebrew origin (06721)', 'Sidon', 'None', 'sid-one\'', 'Noun Location', 'of Hebrew origin («06721»); Sidon (i.e. Tsidon), a place in Palestine:--Sidon.', 'Sidon or Zidon = \"hunting\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>an ancient and wealthy city of Phoenicia, on the east coast of the Mediterranean Sea, less than 20 miles (30 km) north of Tyre</OL>'),
(4606, 'Sidwvnioß', 'from (4605)', 'Sidonios', 'None', 'sid-o\'-nee-os', 'Adjective', 'from «4605»; a Sidonian, i.e. inhabitant of Sidon:--of Sidon.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>an inhabitant of Sidon, a Sidonian</OL>'),
(4607, 'sikavrioß', 'of Latin origin', 'sikarios', '7:278,1026', 'sik-ar\'-ee-os', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Latin origin; a dagger-man or assassin; a freebooter (Jewish fanatic outlawed by the Romans):--murderer. Compare «5406».', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>an assassin<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>one who carries a dagger or short sword under his clothing, that he may kill secretly and treacherously any one he wishes to<LI>a cutthroat</OL></OL>'),
(4608, 'sivkera', 'of Hebrew origin (07941)', 'sikera', 'None', 'sik\'-er-ah', 'Noun Neuter', 'of Hebrew origin («07941»); an intoxicant, i.e. intensely fermented liquor:--strong drink.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>strong drink, an intoxicating beverage, different from wine; it was a artificial product, made of a mixture of sweet ingredients, whether derived from grain and vegetables, or from the juice of fruits (dates), or a decoction of honey</OL>'),
(4609, 'Sila\'ß', 'contraction for (4610)', 'Silas', 'None', 'see\'-las', 'Noun Masculine', 'contraction for «4610»; Silas, a Christian:--Silas.', 'Silas = \"woody\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a Roman citizen, the companion of the apostle Paul on several of his missionary journeys</OL>'),
(4610, 'Silouanovß', 'of Latin origin', 'Silouanos', 'None', 'sil-oo-an-os\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Latin origin; \"silvan\"; Silvanus, a Christian:--Silvanus. Compare «4609».', 'Silas = \"woody\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a Roman citizen, the companion of the apostle Paul on several of his missionary journeys</OL>'),
(4611, 'Silwavm', 'of Hebrew origin (07975)', 'Siloam', 'None', 'sil-o-am\'', 'Noun Location', 'of Hebrew origin («07975»); Siloam (i.e. Shiloach), a pool of Jerusalem:--Siloam.', 'Siloam = \"sent\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the Pool of Siloam, a fountain of water in Jerusalem, also called Shiloah in Isa. 8:<LI>the Tower of Siloam, may have been a tower near or over the Pool of Siloam, which fell down killing 18 men; very likely they were purifying themselves. (Gill)</OL>'),
(4612, 'simikivnqion', 'of Latin origin', 'simikinthion', 'None', 'sim-ee-kin\'-thee-on', 'Noun Neuter', 'of Latin origin; a semicinctium or half-girding, i.e. narrow covering (apron):--apron.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a narrow apron, or linen covering, which workmen and servants were accustomed to wear</OL>'),
(4613, 'Sivmwn', 'of Hebrew origin (08095)', 'Simon', 'None', 'see\'-mone', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Hebrew origin («08095»); Simon (i.e. Shimon), the name of nine Israelites:--Simon. Compare «4826».', 'Peter = \"a rock or stone\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>Peter was one of the apostles<LI>Simon called Zelotes or the Kanaites<LI>Simon, father of Judas who betrayed Jesus.<LI>Simon Magus, the Samaritan wizard<LI>Simon the tanner, Ac.<LI>Simon the Pharisee, Luke 7:40-<LI>Simon of Cyrene who carried the cross of Christ<LI>Simon the cousin of Jesus, the son of Cleophas<LI>Simon the leper, so called to distinguish him from others of the same name</OL>'),
(4614, 'Sinav', 'of Hebrew origin (05514)', 'Sina', '7:282,1026', 'see-nah\'', 'Noun Location', 'of Hebrew origin («05514»); Sina (i.e. Sinai), a mountain in Arabia:--Sina.', 'Sinai = \"thorny\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a mountain or rather a mountainous region in the peninsula of Arabia Petraea, made famous by the giving of the Mosaic law</OL>'),
(4615, 'sivnapi', 'perhaps from sinomai (to hurt, i.e. sting)', 'sinapi', '7:287,1027', 'sin\'-ap-ee', 'Noun Neuter', 'perhaps from sinomai (to hurt, i.e. sting); mustard (the plant):--mustard.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>mustard, the name of a plant which in oriental countries grows from a very small seed and attains to the height of a tree, 10 feet (3 m) and more; hence a very small quantity of a thing is likened to a mustard seed, and also a thing which grows to a remarkable size</OL>'),
(4616, 'sindwvn', 'of uncertain (perhaps foreign) origin', 'sindon', 'None', 'sin-done\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'of uncertain (perhaps foreign) origin; byssos, i.e. bleached linen (the cloth or a garment of it):--(fine) linen (cloth).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>linen cloth, esp. that which was fine and costly, in which the bodies of the dead were wrapped<LI>thing made of fine cloth<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of a light and loose garment worn at night over a naked body</OL></OL>');
INSERT INTO `greek_lexicon` (`number`, `orig_word`, `word_orig`, `translit`, `tdnt`, `phonetic`, `part_of_speech`, `st_def`, `IPD_def`) VALUES
(4617, 'siniavzw', 'from sinion (a sieve)', 'siniazo', '7:291,1028', 'sin-ee-ad\'-zo', 'Verb', 'from sinion (a sieve); to riddle (figuratively):--sift.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to sift, shake in a sieve<LI>fig. by inward agitation to try one\'s faith to the verge of overthrow</OL>'),
(4618, 'sirovß', 'from a derivative of (4621)', 'siteutos', 'None', 'sit-yoo-ros\'', 'Adjective', 'from a derivative of «4621»; grain-fed, i.e. fattened:--fatted.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>fattened, fatted</OL>'),
(4619, 'sitivon', 'from a derivative of (4621)', 'sitistos', 'None', 'sit-is-tos\'', 'Adjective', 'from a derivative of «4621»; grained, i.e. fatted:--fatling.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>fattened</OL>'),
(4620, 'sitomevtrion', 'from (4621) and (3358)', 'sitometron', 'None', 'sit-om\'-et-ron', 'Noun Neuter', 'from «4621» and «3358»; a grain-measure, i.e. (by implication) ration (allowance of food):--portion of meat.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a measured \'portion of\' grain or \'food\'</OL>'),
(4621, 'si\'toß', 'plural irregular neuter sita {see\'-tah}, of uncertain derivation', 'sitos', 'None', 'see\'-tos,', 'Noun Masculine', 'of uncertain derivation; grain, especially wheat:--corn, wheat.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>wheat, grain</OL>'),
(4622, 'Siwvn', 'of Hebrew origin (06726)', 'Sion', '7:292,1028', 'see-own\'', 'Noun Location', 'of Hebrew origin («06726»); Sion (i.e. Tsijon), a hill of Jerusalem; figuratively, the Church (militant or triumphant):--Sion.', 'Sion or Zion = \"a parched place\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the hill on which the higher and more ancient part of Jerusalem was built<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>the southwestern most and highest of the hills on which the city was built</OL><LI>often used of the entire city of Jerusalem<LI>since Jerusalem because the temple stood there, was called the dwelling place of God</OL>'),
(4623, 'siwpavw', 'from siope (silence, i.e. a hush, properly, muteness, i.e. involuntary stillness, or inability to speak, and thus differing from (4602), which is rather a voluntary refusal or indisposition to speak, although the terms are often used synonymously)', 'siopao', 'None', 'see-o-pah\'-o', 'Verb', 'from siope (silence, i.e. a hush; properly, muteness, i.e. involuntary stillness, or inability to speak; and thus differing from «4602», which is rather a voluntary refusal or indisposition to speak, although the terms are often used synonymously); to be dumb (but not deaf also, like 2974 properly); figuratively, to be calm (as quiet water):--dumb, (hold) peace.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to be silent, hold one\'s peace<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>used of one\'s silence because dumb</OL><LI>metaph. of a calm, quiet sea</OL>'),
(4624, 'skandalivzw', 'from (4625)', 'skandalizo', '7:339,1036', 'skan-dal-id\'-zo', 'Verb', 'from «4625»; to entrap, i.e. trip up (figuratively, stumble (transitively) or entice to sin, apostasy or displeasure):--(make to) offend.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to put a stumbling block or impediment in the way, upon which another may trip and fall, metaph. to offend<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to entice to sin<LI>to cause a person to begin to distrust and desert one whom he ought to trust and obey<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to cause to fall away<LI>to be offended in one, i.e. to see in another what I disapprove of and what hinders me from acknowledging his authority<LI>to cause one to judge unfavourably or unjustly of another</OL><LI>since one who stumbles or whose foot gets entangled feels annoyed<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to cause one displeasure at a thing<LI>to make indignant<LI>to be displeased, indignant</OL></OL></OL>'),
(4625, 'skavndalon', 'probably from a derivative of (2578)', 'skandalon', '7:339,1036', 'skan\'-dal-on', 'Noun Neuter', '(\"scandal;\" probably from a derivative of «2578»; a  trap-stick (bent sapling), i.e. snare (figuratively, cause of displeasure or sin):--occasion to fall (of stumbling), offence, thing that offends, stumblingblock.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the movable stick or trigger of a trap, a trap stick<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>a trap, snare<LI>any impediment placed in the way and causing one to stumble or fall, (a stumbling block, occasion of stumbling) i.e. a rock which is a cause of stumbling<LI>fig. applied to Jesus Christ, whose person and career were so contrary to the expectations of the Jews concerning the Messiah, that they rejected him and by their obstinacy made shipwreck of their salvation</OL><LI>any person or thing by which one is (entrapped) drawn into error or sin</OL>'),
(4626, 'skavptw', 'apparently a primary verb', 'skapto', 'None', 'skap\'-to', 'Verb', 'apparently a primary verb; to dig:--dig.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to dig</OL>'),
(4627, 'skavfh', 'a primitive word', 'skaphe', 'None', 'skaf\'-ay', 'Noun Feminine', 'a \"skiff\" (as if dug out), or yawl (carried aboard a large vessel for landing):--boat.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>anything dug out, hollow vessel, trough, tray, tub<LI>of a boat</OL>'),
(4628, 'skevloß', 'apparently from skello (to parch, through the idea of leanness)', 'skelos', 'None', 'skel\'-os', 'Noun Neuter', 'apparently from skello (to parch; through the idea of leanness); the leg (as lank):--leg.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the leg, from the hip to the toes inclusive</OL>'),
(4629, 'skevpasma', 'from a derivative of skepas (a covering', 'skepasma', 'perhaps akin to the base of 4649 through the idea of noticeableness)', 'skep\'-as-mah', 'Neuter', 'from a derivative of skepas (a covering; perhaps akin to the base of «4649» through the idea of noticeableness); clothing:--raiment.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a covering, spec. clothing</OL>'),
(4630, 'Skeua\'ß', 'apparently of Latin origin', 'Skeuas', 'None', 'skyoo-as\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'apparently of Latin origin; left-handed; Scevas (i.e. Scoevus), an Israelite:--Sceva.', 'Sceva = \"mind reader\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a certain chief priest residing at Ephesus</OL>'),
(4631, 'skeuhv', 'from (4632)', 'skeue', 'None', 'skyoo-ay\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «4632»; furniture, i.e. spare tackle:--tackling.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>any apparatus, equipment, or furniture<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of the utensils or tackling of a ship</OL></OL>'),
(4632, 'skeu\'oß', 'of uncertain affinity', 'skeuos', '7:358,1038', 'skyoo\'-os', 'Noun Neuter', 'of uncertain affinity; a vessel, implement, equipment or apparatus (literally or figuratively (specially, a wife as contributing to the usefulness of the husband)):--goods, sail, stuff, vessel.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a vessel<LI>an implement<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>in the plural<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>household utensils, domestic gear<LI>the tackle and armament of vessels, used specifically of sails and ropes</OL></OL><LI>metaph.<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>a man of quality, a chosen instrument<LI>in a bad sense, an assistant in accomplishing an evil deed</OL></OL>\"Vessel\" was a common Greek metaphor for \"body\" since Greeks thoughtof souls living temporarily in bodies.'),
(4633, 'skhnhv', 'apparently akin to (4632) and (4639)', 'skene', '7:368,1040', 'skay-nay\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'apparently akin to «4632» and «4639»; a tent or cloth hut (literally or figuratively):--habitation, tabernacle.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>tent, tabernacle, (made of green boughs, or skins or other materials)<LI>of that well known movable temple of God after the pattern of which the temple at Jerusalem was built</OL>'),
(4634, 'skhnophgiva', 'from (4636) and (4078)', 'skenopegia', '7:390,1040', 'skay-nop-ayg-ee\'-ah', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «4636» and «4078»; the Festival of Tabernacles (so called from the custom of erecting booths for temporary homes):--tabernacles.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the construction of a tabernacle or tabernacles<LI>the feast of tabernacles; this festival was observed by the Jews yearly for seven days, beginning with the 15th of the month Tisri (approx. our Oct.) partly to perpetuate the memory of the time when their ancestors after leaving Egypt dwelt in tents on their way through the Arabian desert, and partly as a season of festivity and joy on the completion of the harvest and the vintage (the festival of ingatherings) In celebrating the festival the Jews were accustomed to construct booths of the leafy branches of trees, -- either on the roofs or in the courts of their dwellings, or in the streets and squares, and to adorn them with flowers and fruits of all kinds -- under which, throughout the period of the festival, they feasted and gave themselves up to rejoicing.</OL>'),
(4635, 'skhnopoiovß', 'from (4633) and (4160)', 'skenopoios', '7:393,1040', 'skay-nop-oy-os\'', 'Adjective', 'from «4633» and «4160»; a manufacturer of tents:--tent-maker.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a tentmaker<LI>one that makes small portable tents, of leather or cloth of goat\'s hair or linen, for the use of travellers</OL>'),
(4636, 'skh\'noß', 'from (4633)', 'skenos', '7:381,1040', 'skay\'-nos', 'Noun Neuter', 'from «4633»; a hut or temporary residence, i.e. (figuratively) the human body (as the abode of the spirit):--tabernacle.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a tabernacle, a tent<LI>metaph. of the human body, in which the soul dwells as in a tent, and which is taken down at death</OL>'),
(4637, 'skhnovw', 'from (4636)', 'skenoo', '7:385,1040', 'skay-no\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4636»; to tent or encamp, i.e. (figuratively) to occupy (as a mansion) or (specially), to reside (as God did in the Tabernacle of old, a symbol of protection and communion):-- dwell.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to fix one\'s tabernacle, have one\'s tabernacle, abide (or live) in a tabernacle (or tent), tabernacle<LI>to dwell</OL>'),
(4638, 'skhvnwma', 'from (4637)', 'skenoma', '7:383,1040', 'skay\'-no-mah', 'Noun Neuter', 'from «4637»; an encampment, i.e. (figuratively) the Temple (as God\'s residence), the body (as a tenement for the soul):-- tabernacle.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a tent, a tabernacle<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of the temple as God\'s habitation<LI>of the tabernacle of the covenant<LI>metaph. of the human body as the dwelling of the soul</OL></OL>'),
(4639, 'skiav', 'apparently a primary word', 'skia', '7:394,1044', 'skee\'-ah', 'Noun Feminine', 'apparently a primary word; \"shade\" or a shadow (literally or figuratively (darkness of error or an adumbration)):-- shadow.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>shadow<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>shade caused by the interception of light<LI>an image cast by an object and representing the form of that object<LI>a sketch, outline, adumbration</OL></OL>'),
(4640, 'skirtavw', 'akin to skairo (to skip)', 'skirtao', '7:401,1046', 'skeer-tah\'-o', 'Verb', 'akin to skairo (to skip); to jump, i.e. sympathetically move (as the quickening of a fetus):--leap (for joy).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to leap</OL>'),
(4641, 'sklhrokardiva', 'from a compound of (4642) and (2588)', 'sklerokardia', '3:613,415', 'sklay-rok-ar-dee\'-ah', 'Noun Feminine', 'feminine of a compound of «4642» and «2588»; hard-heartedness, i.e. (specially), destitution of (spiritual) perception:--hardness of heart.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>hardness of heart</OL>'),
(4642, 'sklhrovß', 'from the base of (4628)', 'skleros', '5:1028,816', 'sklay-ros\'', 'Adjective', 'from the base of «4628»; dry, i.e. hard or tough (figuratively, harsh, severe):--fierce, hard.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>hard, harsh, rough, stiff<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of men: metaph. harsh, stern, hard<LI>of things: violent, rough, offensive, intolerable</OL></OL>'),
(4643, 'sklhrovthß', 'from (4642)', 'sklerotes', '5:1028,816', 'sklay-rot\'-ace', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «4642»; callousness, i.e. (figuratively) stubbornness:--hardness.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>hardness<LI>obstinacy, stubbornness</OL>'),
(4644, 'sklhrotravchloß', 'from (4642) and (5137)', 'sklerotrachelos', '5:1029,816', 'sklay-rot-rakh\'-ay-los', 'Adjective', 'from «4642» and «5137»; hardnaped, i.e. (figuratively) obstinate:--stiffnecked.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>stiffnecked<LI>stubborn, headstrong, obstinate</OL>'),
(4645, 'sklhruvnw', 'from (4642)', 'skleruno', '5:1030,816', 'sklay-roo\'-no', 'Verb', 'from «4642»; to indurate, i.e. (figuratively) render stubborn:--harden.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to make hard, harden<LI>metaph.<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to render obstinate, stubborn<LI>to be hardened<LI>to become obstinate or stubborn</OL></OL>'),
(4646, 'skoliovß', 'from the base of (4628)', 'skolios', '7:403,1046', 'skol-ee-os\'', 'Adjective', 'from the base of «4628»; warped, i.e. winding; figuratively, perverse:--crooked, froward, untoward.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>crooked, curved<LI>metaph.<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>perverse, wicked<LI>unfair, surly, froward</OL></OL>'),
(4647, 'skovloy', 'perhaps from the base of (4628) and (3700)', 'skolops', '7:409,1047', 'skol\'-ops', 'Noun Masculine', 'perhaps from the base of «4628» and «3700»; withered at the front, i.e. a point or prickle (figuratively, a bodily annoyance or disability):--thorn.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a pointed piece of wood, a pale, a stake<LI>a sharp stake, splinter</OL>'),
(4648, 'skopevw', 'from (4649)', 'skopeo', '7:414,1047', 'skop-eh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4649»; to take aim at (spy), i.e. (figuratively) regard:--consider, take heed, look at (on), mark. Compare «3700».', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to look at, observe, contemplate<LI>to mark<LI>to fix one\'s eyes upon, direct one\'s attention to, any one<LI>to look to, take heed to thyself</OL>'),
(4649, 'skopovß', 'from skeptomai (to peer about [\"skeptic\"], perhaps akin to (4626) through the idea of concealment, cf (4629))', 'skopos', '7:413,1047', 'skop-os\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'from skeptomai (to peer about (\"skeptic\"); perhaps akin to «4626» through the idea of concealment; compare «4629»); a watch (sentry or scout), i.e. (by implication) a goal:--mark.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>an observer, a watchman<LI>the distant mark looked at, the goal or end one has in view</OL>'),
(4650, 'skorpivzw', 'apparently from the same as (4651) (through the idea of penetrating)', 'skorpizo', '7:418,1048', 'skor-pid\'-zo', 'Verb', 'apparently from the same as «4651» (through the idea of penetrating); to dissipate, i.e. (figuratively) put to flight, waste, be liberal:--disperse abroad, scatter (abroad).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to scatter<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of those who, routed or terror stricken or driven by some other impulses, fly in every direction<LI>to scatter abroad (what others may collect for themselves), or one dispensing blessings literally</OL></OL>'),
(4651, 'skorpivoß', 'probably from an obsolete skerpo (perhaps strengthened from the base of (4649) and meaning to pierce)', 'skorpios', 'None', 'skor-pee\'-os', 'Noun Masculine', 'probably from an obsolete skerpo (perhaps strengthened from the base of «4649» and meaning to pierce); a \"scorpion\" (from its sting):--scorpion.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a scorpion, the name of a little animal, somewhat resembling a lobster, which in warm regions lurk, esp. in stone walls; it has a poisonous sting in its tail</OL>'),
(4652, 'skoteinovß', 'from (4655)', 'skoteinos', '7:423,1049', 'skot-i-nos\'', 'Adjective', 'from «4655»; opaque, i.e. (figuratively) benighted:--dark, full of darkness.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>full of darkness, covered with darkness</OL>'),
(4653, 'skotiva', 'from (4655)', 'skotia', '7:423,1049', 'skot-ee\'-ah', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «4655»; dimness, obscurity (literally or figuratively):--dark(-ness).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>darkness<LI>the darkness due to want of light<LI>metaph. used of ignorance of divine things, and its associated wickedness, and the resultant misery in hell</OL>'),
(4654, 'skotivzw', 'from (4655)', 'skotizo', '7:423,1049', 'skot-id-zo', 'Verb', 'from «4655»; to obscure (literally or figuratively):--darken.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to cover with darkness, to darken<LI>to be covered with darkness, be darkened<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of heavenly bodies as deprived of light<LI>metaph.<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>of the eyes<LI>of the understanding<LI>of the mind</OL></OL></OL>'),
(4655, 'skovtoß', 'from the base of (4639)', 'skotos', '7:423,1049', 'skot\'-os', 'Noun Neuter', 'from the base of «4639»; shadiness, i.e. obscurity (literally or figuratively):--darkness.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>darkness<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of night darkness<LI>of darkened eyesight or blindness</OL><LI>metaph.<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of ignorance respecting divine things and human duties, and the accompanying ungodliness and immorality, together with their consequent misery in hell<LI>persons in whom darkness becomes visible and holds sway</OL></OL>'),
(4656, 'skotovw', 'from (4655)', 'skotoo', '7:423,1049', 'skot-o\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4655»; to obscure or blind (literally or figuratively):--be full of darkness.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to darken, cover with darkness<LI>metaph. to darken or blind the mind</OL>'),
(4657, 'skuvbalon', 'neuter of a presumed derivative of (1519) and (2965) and (906)', 'skubalon', '7:445,1052', 'skoo\'-bal-on', 'Noun Neuter', 'neuter of a presumed derivative of «1519» and «2965» and «906»; what is thrown to the dogs, i.e. refuse (ordure):--dung.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>any refuse, as the excrement of animals, offscourings, rubbish, dregs<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of things worthless and detestable</OL></OL>'),
(4658, 'Skuvqhß', 'probably of foreign origin', 'Skuthes', '7:447,1053', 'skoo\'-thace', 'Noun Masculine', 'probably of foreign origin; a Scythene or Scythian, i.e. (by implication) a savage:--Scythian.', 'Scythian = \"rude or rough\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a Scythian, an inhabitant of Scythia or modern day Russia<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>by the more civilised nations of antiquity the Scythians were regarded as the wildest of barbarians</OL></OL>'),
(4659, 'skuqrwpovß', 'from skuthros (sullen) and a derivative of (3700)', 'skuthropos', '7:450,1053', 'skoo-thro-pos\'', 'Adjective', 'from skuthros (sullen) and a derivative of «3700»; angry-visaged, i.e. gloomy or affecting a mournful appearance:--of a sad countenance.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>of a sad and gloomy countenance</OL>'),
(4660, 'skuvllw', 'apparently a primary verb', 'skullo', 'None', 'skool\'-lo', 'Verb', 'apparently a primary verb; to flay, i.e. (figuratively) to harass:--trouble(self).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to skin, flay<LI>to rend, mangle<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to vex, trouble, annoy<LI>to give one\'s self trouble, trouble one\'s self</OL></OL>'),
(4661, 'sku\'lon', 'from (4660)', 'skulon', 'None', 'skoo\'-lon', 'Noun Neuter', 'neuter from «4660»; something stripped (as a hide), i.e. booty:--spoil.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a (beast\'s) skin stripped off, a pelt<LI>the weapons and valuables stripped off from an enemy, spoils</OL>'),
(4662, 'skwlhkovbrwtoß', 'from (4663) and a derivative of (977)', 'skolekobrotos', '7:456,1054', 'sko-lay-kob\'-ro-tos', 'Adjective', 'from «4663» and a derivative of «977»; worm-eaten, i.e. diseased with maggots:--eaten of worms.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>eaten of worms</OL>'),
(4663, 'skwvlhx', 'of uncertain derivation', 'skolex', '7:452,1054', 'sko\'-lakes', 'Noun Masculine', 'of uncertain derivation; a grub, maggot or earth-worm:--worm.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a worm, spec. that kind which preys upon dead bodies</OL>'),
(4664, 'smaravgdinoß', 'from (4665)', 'smaragdinos', 'None', 'smar-ag\'-dee-nos', 'Adjective', 'from «4665»; consisting of emerald:--emerald.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>of emerald, made of emerald</OL>'),
(4665, 'smavragdoß', 'of uncertain derivation', 'smaragdos', 'None', 'smar\'-ag-dos', 'Noun Feminine', 'of uncertain derivation; the emerald or green gem so called:--emerald.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a transparent precious stone noted especially for its light green colour</OL>'),
(4666, 'smuvrna', 'apparently strengthened for (3464)', 'smurna', '7:457,1055', 'smoor\'-nah', 'Noun Feminine', 'apparently strengthened for «3464»; myrrh:--myrrh.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>myrrh, a bitter gum and costly perfume which exudes from a certain tree or shrub in Arabia and Ethiopia, or is obtained by incisions made in the bark: as an antiseptic it was used for embalming</OL>'),
(4667, 'Smuvrna', 'the same as (4666)', 'Smurna', 'None', 'smoor\'-nah', 'Noun Location', 'the same as «4666»; Smyrna, a place in Asia Minor:--Smyrna.', 'Smyrna = \"myrrh\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>an Ionian city of Asia Minor, on the Aegean Sea, 40 miles (65 km) north of Ephesus</OL>'),
(4668, 'Smurnai\'oß', 'from (4667)', 'Smurnaios', 'None', 'smoor-nah\'-yos', 'Adjective', 'from «4667»; a Smyrnoean:--in Smyrna.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>of or belonging to Smyrna, an inhabitant of Smyrna</OL>'),
(4669, 'smurnivzw', 'from (4667)', 'smurnizo', '7:458,1055', 'smoor-nid\'-zo', 'Verb', 'from «4667»; to tincture with myrrh, i.e. embitter (as a narcotic):--mingle with myrrh.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to be like myrrh<LI>to mix and so flavour with myrrh<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>wine with myrrh: i.e. wine flavoured with myrrh. The ancients used to infuse myrrh into wine to give it a more agreeable fragrance and flavour</OL></OL>'),
(4670, 'Sovdoma', 'plural of Hebrew origin (05467)', 'Sodoma', 'None', 'sod\'-om-ah', 'Noun Location', 'plural of Hebrew origin («05467»); Sodoma (i.e. Sedom), a place in Palestine:--Sodom.', 'Sodom = \"burning\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a city destroyed by the Lord raining fire and brimstone on it<LI>metaph. Jerusalem Rev. 11:8</OL>'),
(4671, 'soiv', 'dative case of (4771)', 'soi', 'None', 'soy', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to you</OL>', 'dative case of «4771»; to thee:--thee, thine own, thou, thy.', ''),
(4672, 'Solomwvn', 'of Hebrew origin (08010)', 'Solomon', '7:459,1055', 'sol-om-one\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Hebrew origin («08010»); Solomon (i.e. Shelomoh), the son of David:--Solomon.', 'Solomon = \"peaceful\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the son of David and was the wisest and richest king that ever lived</OL>'),
(4673, 'sorovß', 'probably akin to the base of (4987)', 'soros', 'None', 'sor-os\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'probably akin to the base of «4987»; a funereal receptacle (urn, coffin), i.e. (by analogy) a bier:--bier.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>an urn or receptacle for keeping the bones of the dead<LI>the funeral couch or bier on which the Jews carried their dead forth to burial</OL>'),
(4674, 'sovß', 'from (4771)', 'sos', 'None', 'sos', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>thy, thine</OL>', 'from «4771»; thine:--thine (own), thy (friend).', ''),
(4675, 'sou\'', 'genitive case of (4771)', 'sou', 'None', 'soo', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>thy, thee</OL>', 'genitive case of «4771»; of thee, thy:--X home, thee, thine (own), thou, thy.', ''),
(4676, 'soudavrion', 'of Latin origin', 'soudarion', 'None', 'soo-dar\'-ee-on', 'Noun Neuter', 'of Latin origin; a sudarium (sweat-cloth), i.e. towel (for wiping the perspiration from the face, or binding the face of a corpse):--handkerchief, napkin.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a handkerchief<LI>a cloth for wiping perspiration from the face and for cleaning the nose and also used in swathing the head of a corpse</OL>'),
(4677, 'Sousavnna', 'of Hebrew origin (07799) feminine', 'Sousanna', 'None', 'soo-san\'-nah', 'Noun Feminine', 'of Hebrew origin (7799 feminine); lily; Susannah (i.e. Shoshannah), an Israelitess:--Susanna.', 'Susanna = \"a lily\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>one of the women who ministered to Christ</OL>'),
(4678, 'sofiva', 'from (4680)', 'sophia', '7:465,1056', 'sof-ee\'-ah', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «4680»; wisdom (higher or lower, worldly or spiritual):--wisdom.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>wisdom, broad and full of intelligence; used of the knowledge of very diverse matters<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>the wisdom which belongs to men<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>spec. the varied knowledge of things human and divine, acquired by acuteness and experience, and summed up in maxims and proverbs<LI>the science and learning<LI>the act of interpreting dreams and always giving the sagest advice<LI>the intelligence evinced in discovering the meaning of some mysterious number or vision<LI>skill in the management of affairs<LI>devout and proper prudence in intercourse with men not disciples of Christ, skill and discretion in imparting Christian truth<LI>the knowledge and practice of the requisites for godly and upright living</OL><LI>supreme intelligence, such as belongs to God<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to Christ<LI>the wisdom of God as evinced in forming and executing counsels in the formation and government of the world and the scriptures</OL></OL></OL>'),
(4679, 'sofivzw', 'from (4680)', 'sophizo', '7:527,1056', 'sof-id\'-zo', 'Verb', 'from «4680»; to render wise; in a sinister acceptation, to form \"sophisms\", i.e. continue plausible error:--cunningly devised, make wise.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to make wise, teach<LI>to become wise, to have understanding<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to invent, play the sophist<LI>to devise cleverly or cunningly</OL></OL>'),
(4680, 'sofovß', 'akin to saphes (clear)', 'sophos', '7:465,1056', 'sof-os\'', 'Adjective', 'akin to saphes (clear); wise (in a most general application):--wise. Compare «5429».', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>wise<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>skilled, expert: of artificers<LI>wise, skilled in letters, cultivated, learned<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>of the Greek philosophers and orators<LI>of Jewish theologians<LI>of Christian teachers</OL><LI>forming the best plans and using the best means for their execution</OL></OL>'),
(4681, 'Spaniva', 'probably of foreign origin', 'Spania', 'None', 'span-ee\'-ah', 'Noun Location', 'probably of foreign origin; Spania, a region of Europe:--Spain.', 'Spain = \"scarceness\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the whole peninsula south of the Pyrenees</OL>'),
(4682, 'sparavssw', 'prolongation from spairo (to grasp, apparently strengthened from (4685) through the idea of spasmodic contraction)', 'sparasso', 'None', 'spar-as\'-so', 'Verb', 'prolongation from spairo (to grasp; apparently strengthened from «4685» through the idea of spasmodic contraction); to mangle, i.e. convluse with epilepsy:--rend, tear.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to convulse, tear</OL>'),
(4683, 'sparganovw', 'from sparganon (a strip, from a derivative of the base of (4682) meaning to strap or wrap with strips)', 'sparganoo', 'None', 'spar-gan-o\'-o', 'Verb', 'from sparganon (a strip; from a derivative of the base of «4682» meaning to strap or wrap with strips); to swathe (an infant after the Oriental custom):--wrap in swaddling clothes.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to wrap in swaddling clothes<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of an infant just born</OL></OL>'),
(4684, 'spatalavw', 'from spatale (luxury)', 'spatalao', 'None', 'spat-al-ah\'-o', 'Verb', 'from spatale (luxury); to be voluptuous:--live in pleasure, be wanton.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to live luxuriously, lead a voluptuous life, (give one\'s self to pleasure)</OL>'),
(4685, 'spavw', 'a primary verb', 'spao', 'None', 'spah\'-o', 'Verb', 'a primary verb; to draw:--draw (out).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to draw<LI>to draw (one\'s sword)</OL>'),
(4686, 'spei\'ra', 'of immed. Latin origin, but ultimately a derivative of (138) in the sense of its cognate (1507)', 'speira', 'None', 'spi\'-rah', 'Noun Feminine', 'of immediate Latin origin, but ultimately a derivative of «138» in the sense of its cognate «1507»; a coil (spira, \"spire\"), i.e. (figuratively) a mass of men (a Roman military cohort; also (by analogy) a squad of Levitical janitors):--band.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>anything rolled into a circle or ball, anything wound, rolled up, folded together<LI>a military cohort<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>the tenth part of legion<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>about 600 men i.e. legionaries<LI>if auxiliaries either 500 or 1000<LI>a maniple, or the thirtieth part of a legion</OL><LI>any band, company, or detachment, of soldiers</OL></OL>'),
(4687, 'speivrw', 'probably strengthened from (4685) (through the idea of extending)', 'speiro', '7:536,1065', 'spi\'-ro', 'Verb', 'probably strengthened from «4685» (through the idea of extending); to scatter, i.e. sow (literally or figuratively):--sow(- er), receive seed.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to sow, scatter, seed<LI>metaph. of proverbial sayings</OL>'),
(4688, 'spekoulavtwr', 'of Latin origin', 'spekoulator', 'None', 'spek-oo-lat\'-ore', 'Noun Masculine', 'of Latin origin; a speculator, i.e. military scout (spy or (by extension) life-guardsman):--executioner.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a spy, scout<LI>under the emperors an attendant and member of the body guard, employed as messengers, watchers, and executioners<LI>the name is transferred to an attendant of Herod Antipas that acted as executioner</OL>'),
(4689, 'spevndw', 'apparently a primary verb', 'spendo', '7:528,*', 'spen\'-do', 'Verb', 'apparently a primary verb; to pour out as a libation, i.e. (figuratively) to devote (one\'s life or blood, as a sacrifice) (\"spend\"):--(be ready to) be offered.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to pour out as a drink offering, make a libation<LI>in the NT to be offered as a libation<LI>fig. used of one whose blood is poured out in a violent death for the cause of God</OL>'),
(4690, 'spevrma', 'from (4687)', 'sperma', '7:536,1065', 'sper\'-mah', 'Noun Neuter', 'from «4687»; something sown, i.e. seed (including the male \"sperm\"); by implication, offspring; specially, a remnant (figuratively, as if kept over for planting):--issue, seed.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>from which a plant germinates<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>the seed i.e. the grain or kernel which contains within itself the germ of the future plants<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>of the grains or kernels sown</OL><LI>metaph. a seed i.e. a residue, or a few survivors reserved as the germ of the next generation (just as seed is kept from the harvest for the sowing)</OL><LI>the semen virile<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>the product of this semen, seed, children, offspring, progeny<LI>family, tribe, posterity<LI>whatever possesses vital force or life giving power<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>of divine energy of the Holy Spirit operating within the soul by which we are regenerated</OL></OL></OL>'),
(4691, 'spermolovgoß', 'from (4690) and (3004)', 'spermologos', 'None', 'sper-mol-og\'-os', 'Adjective', 'from «4690» and «3004»; a seed-picker (as the crow), i.e. (figuratively) a sponger, loafer (specially, a gossip or trifler in talk):--babbler.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>picking up seed<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of birds, esp. of the crow or daw that picks up grain in fields</OL><LI>metaph.<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>lounging about the market place and picking up a substance by whatever may chance to fall from the loads of merchandise<LI>hence, beggarly, abject, vile, (a parasite)<LI>getting a living by flattery and bufferoonery<LI>an empty talker, babbler</OL></OL>'),
(4692, 'speuvdw', 'probably strengthened from (4228)', 'speudo', 'None', 'spyoo\'-do', 'Verb', 'probably strengthened from «4228»; to \"speed\" (\"study\"), i.e. urge on (diligently or earnestly); by implication, to await eagerly:--(make, with) haste unto.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to haste, make haste<LI>to desire earnestly</OL>'),
(4693, 'sphvlaion', 'from a presumed derivative of speos (a grotto)', 'spelaion', 'None', 'spay\'-lah-yon', 'Noun Neuter', 'neuter of a presumed derivative of speos (a grotto); a cavern; by implication, a hiding-place or resort:--cave, den.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a cave, den</OL>'),
(4694, 'spilavß', 'of uncertain derivation', 'spilas', 'None', 'spee-las\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'of uncertain derivation; a ledge or reef of rock in the sea:--spot (by confusion with «4696»).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a rock in the sea, ledge, reef<LI>metaph. of men who by their conduct damage others morally, wreck them as it were</OL>'),
(4695, 'spilovw', 'from (4696)', 'spiloo', 'None', 'spee-lo\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4696»; to stain or soil (literally or figuratively):--defile, spot.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to defile, spot</OL>'),
(4696, 'spivloß', 'of uncertain derivation', 'spilos', 'None', 'spee\'-los', 'Noun Masculine', 'of uncertain derivation; a stain or blemish, i.e. (figuratively) defect, disgrace:--spot.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a spot<LI>a fault, moral blemish<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of base and gluttonous men</OL></OL>'),
(4697, 'splagcnivzomai', 'middle voice from (4698)', 'splagchnizomai', '7:548,1067', 'splangkh-nid\'-zom-ahee', 'Verb', 'middle voice from «4698»; to have the bowels yearn, i.e. (figuratively) feel sympathy, to pity:--have (be moved with) compassion.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to be moved as to one\'s bowels, hence to be moved with compassion, have compassion (for the bowels were thought to be the seat of love and pity)</OL>'),
(4698, 'splavgcnon', 'probably strengthened from splen (the \"spleen\")', 'splagchnon', '7:548,1067', 'splangkh\'-non', 'Noun Neuter', 'probably strengthened from splen (the \"spleen\"); an intestine (plural); figuratively, pity or sympathy:--bowels, inward affection, + tender mercy.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>bowels, intestines, (the heart, lungs, liver, etc.)<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>bowels<LI>the bowels were regarded as the seat of the more violent passions, such as anger and love; but by the Hebrews as the seat of the tenderer affections, esp. kindness, benevolence, compassion; hence our heart (tender mercies, affections, etc.)<LI>a heart in which mercy resides</OL></OL>'),
(4699, 'spovggoß', 'perhaps of foreign origin', 'spoggos', 'None', 'spong\'-gos', 'Noun Masculine', 'perhaps of foreign origin; a \"sponge\":--spunge.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>sponge</OL>'),
(4700, 'spodovß', 'of uncertain derivation', 'spodos', 'None', 'spod-os\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'of uncertain derivation; ashes:--ashes.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>ashes: placed on sackcloth as a token of grief</OL>'),
(4701, 'sporav', 'from (4687)', 'spora', '7:536,1065', 'spor-ah\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «4687»; a sowing, i.e. (by implication) parentage:--seed.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>seed</OL>'),
(4702, 'spovrimoß', 'from (4703)', 'sporimos', '7:536,1065', 'spor\'-ee-mos', 'Adjective', 'from «4703»; sown, i.e. (neuter plural) a planted field:--corn(-field).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>fit for sowing, sown<LI>sown fields, growing crops</OL>'),
(4703, 'spovroß', 'from (4687)', 'sporos', '7:536,1065', 'spro\'-os', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «4687»; a scattering (of seed), i.e. (concretely) seed (as sown):--seed (X sown).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a sowing<LI>seed (used in sowing)</OL>'),
(4704, 'spoudavzw', 'from (4710)', 'spoudazo', '7:559,1069', 'spoo-dad\'-zo', 'Verb', 'from «4710»; to use speed, i.e. to make effort, be prompt or earnest:--do (give) diligence, be diligent (forward), endeavour, labour, study.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to hasten, make haste<LI>to exert one\'s self, endeavour, give diligence</OL>'),
(4705, 'spoudai\'oß', 'from (4710)', 'spoudaios', '7:559,1069', 'spoo-dah\'-yos', 'Adjective', 'from «4710»; prompt, energetic, earnest:--diligent.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>active, diligent, zealous, earnest<LI>very diligent</OL>'),
(4706, 'spoudaiovteron', 'neuter of (4707) as adverb', 'spoudaioteron', 'None', 'spoo-dah-yot\'-er-on', 'Adjective', 'neuter of «4707» as adverb; more earnestly than others), i.e. very promptly:--very diligently.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>very diligently</OL>'),
(4707, 'spoudaiovteroß', 'comparative of (4705)', 'spoudaioteros', 'None', 'spoo-dah-yot\'-er-os', 'Adjective', 'comparative of «4705»; more prompt, more earnest:--more diligent (forward).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>active, diligent, zealous, earnest<LI>very diligent</OL>'),
(4708, 'spoudaiotevrwß', 'from (4707)', 'spoudaioteros', 'None', 'spoo-dah-yot-er\'-oce', 'Adverb', 'adverb from «4707»; more speedily, i.e. sooner than otherwise:--more carefully.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>hastily, with haste<LI>diligently, earnestly</OL>'),
(4709, 'spoudaivwß', 'from (4705)', 'spoudaios', 'None', 'spoo-dah\'-yoce', 'Adverb', 'adverb from «4705»; earnestly, promptly:--diligently, instantly.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>hastily, with haste<LI>diligently<LI>earnestly</OL>'),
(4710, 'spoudhv', 'from (4692)', 'spoude', '7:559,1069', 'spoo-day\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «4692»; \"speed\", i.e. (by implication) despatch, eagerness, earnestness:--business, (earnest) care(-fulness), diligence, forwardness, haste.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>haste, with haste<LI>earnestness, diligence<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>earnestness in accomplishing, promoting, or striving after anything<LI>to give all diligence, interest one\'s self most earnestly</OL></OL>'),
(4711, 'spurivß', 'from (4687) (as woven)', 'spuris', 'None', 'spoo-rece\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «4687» (as woven); a hamper or lunch-receptacle:--basket.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a reed basket, (a plaited basket, a lunch basket, hamper)</OL>'),
(4712, 'stavdion', 'or masculine (in plural) stadios {stad\'-ee-os}, from the base of (2476) (as fixed)', 'stadion', 'None', 'stad\'-ee-on,', 'Noun Neuter', 'from the base of «2476» (as fixed); a stade or certain measure of distance; by implication, a stadium or race-course:--furlong, race.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a space or distance of about 600 feet (185 m)<LI>a race course<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>place in which contests in running were held, the one who outstripped the rest and reached the goal first, receiving the prize. Courses of this description were found in most of the larger Greek cities, and were like that at Olympia, 600 Greek feet in length</OL></OL>'),
(4713, 'stavmnoß', 'from the base of (2476) (as stationary)', 'stamnos', 'None', 'stam\'-nos', 'Noun Feminine', 'from the base of «2476» (as stationary); a jar or earthen tank:--pot.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>among the Greeks an earthen jar, into which wine was drawn off for keeping but also used for other purposes<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of the little jar in which the manna was kept, laid up in the ark of the covenant</OL></OL>'),
(4714, 'stasiasthvß', 'from the base of (2476)', 'stasis', '7:568,1070', 'stas\'-is', 'Noun Feminine', 'from the base of «2476»; a standing (properly, the act), i.e. (by analogy) position (existence); by implication, a popular uprising; figuratively, controversy:--dissension, insurrection, × standing, uproar.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a standing, station, state<LI>an insurrection<LI>strife, insurrection</OL>'),
(4715, 'stathvr', 'from the base of (2746)', 'stater', 'None', 'stat-air\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'from the base of «2746»; a stander (standard of value), i.e. (specially), a stater or certain coin:--piece of money.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a stater, a coin<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>in the NT a silver stater equal to four Attic or two Alexandrian drachmas, a Jewish shekel</OL></OL>'),
(4716, 'staurovß', 'from the base of (2476)', 'stauros', '7:572,1071', 'stow-ros\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'from the base of «2476»; a stake or post (as set upright), i.e. (specially), a pole or cross (as an instrument of capital punishment); figuratively, exposure to death, i.e. self-denial; by implication, the atonement of Christ:--cross.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>an upright stake, esp. a pointed one<LI>a cross<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>a well known instrument of most cruel and ignominious punishment, borrowed by the Greeks and Romans from the Phoenicians; to it were affixed among the Romans, down to the time of Constantine the Great, the guiltiest criminals, particularly the basest slaves, robbers, the authors and abetters of insurrections, and occasionally in the provinces, at the arbitrary pleasure of the governors, upright and peaceable men also, and even Roman citizens themselves<LI>the crucifixion which Christ underwent</OL></OL>'),
(4717, 'staurovw', 'from (4716)', 'stauroo', '7:581,1071', 'stow-ro\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4716»; to impale on the cross; figuratively, to extinguish (subdue) passion or selfishness:--crucify.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to stake, drive down stakes<LI>to fortify with driven stakes, to palisade<LI>to crucify<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to crucify one<LI>metaph. to crucify the flesh, destroy its power utterly (the nature of the figure implying that the destruction is attended with intense pain)</OL></OL>'),
(4718, 'stafulhv', 'probably from the base of (4735)', 'staphule', 'None', 'staf-oo-lay\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'probably from the base of «4735»; a cluster of grapes (as if intertwined):--grapes.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>grapes, bunch of grapes</OL>'),
(4719, 'stavcuß', 'from the base of (2476)', 'stachus', 'None', 'stakh\'-oos', 'Noun Masculine', 'from the base of «2476»; a head of grain (as standing out from the stalk):--ear (of corn).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>an ear of corn or of growing grain</OL>'),
(4720, 'Stavcuß', 'the same as (4719)', 'Stachus', 'None', 'stakh\'-oos', 'Noun Masculine', 'the same as «4719»; Stachys, a Christian:--Stachys.', 'Stachys = \"a head of grain\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a man with a Greek name, he is said to be one of the seventy disciples, and bishop of Byzantium (Gill)</OL>'),
(4721, 'stevgh', 'strengthened from a primary tegos (a \"thatch\" or \"deck\" of a building)', 'stege', 'None', 'steg\'-ay', 'Noun Feminine', 'strengthened from a primary tegos (a \"thatch\" or \"deck\" of a building); a roof:--roof.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a roof: of a house</OL>'),
(4722, 'stevgw', 'from (4721)', 'stego', '7:585,1073', 'steg\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4721»; to roof over, i.e. (figuratively) to cover with silence (endure patiently):--(for-)bear, suffer.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>deck, thatch, to cover<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to protect or keep by covering, to preserve</OL><LI>to cover over with silence<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to keep secret<LI>to hide, conceal<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>of the errors and faults of others</OL></OL><LI>by covering to keep off something which threatens, to bear up against, hold out against, and so endure, bear, forbear</OL>'),
(4723, 'stei\'ra', 'a contraction from (4731) (as stiff and unnatural)', 'steiros', 'None', 'sti\'-ros', 'Adjective', 'a contraction from «4731» (as stiff and unnatural); \"sterile\":--barren.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>hard, stiff<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of men and animals</OL><LI>barren<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of woman who does not conceive</OL></OL>'),
(4724, 'stevllw', 'probably strengthened from the base of (2476)', 'stello', '7:588,1074', 'stel\'-lo', 'Verb', 'probably strengthened from the base of «2476»; properly, to set fast (\"stall\"), i.e. (figuratively) to repress (reflexively, abstain from associating with):--avoid, withdraw self.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to set, place, set in order, arrange<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to fit out, to prepare, equip<LI>to prepare one\'s self, to fit out for one\'s self<LI>to fit out for one\'s own use<LI>to prepare one\'s self, to fit out for one\'s self<LI>to fit out for one\'s own use<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>arranging, providing for this, etc.</OL></OL><LI>to bring together, contract, shorten<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to diminish, check, cause to cease<LI>to cease to exist<LI>to remove one\'s self, withdraw one\'s self, to depart<LI>to abstain from familiar intercourse with one</OL></OL>'),
(4725, 'stevmma', 'from the base of (4735)', 'stemma', 'None', 'stem\'-mah', 'Noun Neuter', 'from the base of «4735»; a wreath for show:--garland.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a fillet, a garland, put upon victims</OL>'),
(4726, 'stenagmovß', 'from (4727)', 'stenagmos', '7:600,1076', 'sten-ag-mos\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «4727»; a sigh:--groaning.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a groaning, a sigh</OL>'),
(4727, 'stenavzw', 'from (4728)', 'stenazo', '7:600,1076', 'sten-ad\'-zo', 'Verb', 'from «4728»; to make (intransitively, be) in straits, i.e. (by implication) to sigh, murmur, pray inaudibly:--with grief, groan, grudge, sigh.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a sigh, to groan</OL>'),
(4728, 'stenovß', 'probably from the base of (2476)', 'stenos', '7:604,1077', 'sten-os\'', 'Adjective', 'probably from the base of «2476»; narrow (from obstacles standing close about):--strait.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>narrow, strait</OL>'),
(4729, 'stenocwrevw', 'from the same as (4730)', 'stenochoreo', '7:604,1077', 'sten-okh-o-reh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from the same as «4730»; to hem in closely, i.e. (figuratively) cramp:--distress, straiten.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to be in a narrow place<LI>to straiten, compress, cramp, reduce to straits<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to be sorely straitened in spirit</OL></OL>'),
(4730, 'stenocwriva', 'from a compound of (4728) and (5561)', 'stenochoria', '7:604,1077', 'sten-okh-o-ree\'-ah', 'Noun Feminine', 'from a compound of «4728» and «5561»; narrowness of room, i.e. (figuratively) calamity:--anguish, distress.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>narrowness of place, a narrow place<LI>metaph. dire calamity, extreme affliction</OL>'),
(4731, 'stereovß', 'from (2476)', 'stereos', '7:609,1077', 'ster-eh-os\'', 'Adjective', 'from «2476»; stiff, i.e. solid, stable (literally or figuratively):--stedfast, strong, sure.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>strong, firm, immovable, solid, hard, rigid<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>in a bad sense, cruel, stiff, stubborn, hard<LI>in a good sense, firm, steadfast</OL></OL>'),
(4732, 'stereovw', 'from (4731)', 'stereoo', '7:609,1077', 'ster-eh-o\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4731»; to solidify, i.e. confirm (literally or figuratively):--establish, receive strength, make strong.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to make solid, make firm, strengthen, make strong<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of the body of anyone</OL></OL>'),
(4733, 'sterevwma', 'from (4732)', 'stereoma', '7:609,1077', 'ster-eh\'-o-mah', 'Noun Neuter', 'from «4732»; something established, i.e. (abstractly) confirmation (stability):--stedfastness.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>that which has been made firm<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>the firmament, the arch of the sky, which in early times was thought to be solid<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a fortified place</OL><LI>that which furnishes a foundation<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>on which a thing rests firmly, support</OL><LI>firmness, steadfastness<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>metaph. in a military sense: solid front</OL></OL></OL>'),
(4734, 'Stefana\'ß', 'probably contraction for stephanotos (crowned, from (4737))', 'Stephanas', 'None', 'stef-an-as\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'probably contraction for stephanotos (crowned; from «4737»); Stephanas, a Christian:--Stephanas.', 'Stephanas = \"crowned\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a Christian convert of Corinth</OL>'),
(4735, 'stevfanoß', 'from an apparently primary stepho (to twine or wreathe)', 'stephanos', '7:615,1078', 'stef\'-an-os', 'Noun Masculine', 'from an apparently primary stepho (to twine or wreathe); a chaplet (as a badge of royalty, a prize in the public games or a symbol of honor generally; but more conspicuous and elaborate than the simple fillet, «1238»), literally or figuratively:--crown.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a crown<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>a mark of royal or (in general) exalted rank<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the wreath or garland which was given as a prize to victors in public games</OL><LI>metaph. the eternal blessedness which will be given as a prize to the genuine servants of God and Christ: the crown (wreath) which is the reward of the righteousness<LI>that which is an ornament and honour to one</OL></OL>'),
(4736, 'Stevfanoß', 'the same as (4735)', 'Stephanos', 'None', 'stef\'-an-os', 'Noun Masculine', 'the same as «4735»; Stephanus, a Christian:--Stephen.', 'Stephen = \"crowned\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>one of the seven deacons in Jerusalem and the first Christian martyr</OL>'),
(4737, 'stefanovw', 'from (4735)', 'stephanoo', '7:615,1078', 'stef-an-o\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4735»; to adorn with an honorary wreath (literally or figuratively):--crown.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to encircle with a crown, to crown: the victor in a contest<LI>to adorn, to honour</OL>'),
(4738, 'sth\'qoß', 'from (2476) (as standing prominently)', 'stethos', 'None', 'stay\'-thos', 'Noun Neuter', 'from «2476» (as standing prominently); the (entire external) bosom, i.e. chest:--breast.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the breast</OL>'),
(4739, 'sthvkw', 'from the perfect tense of (2476)', 'steko', '7:636,1082', 'stay\'-ko', 'Verb', 'from the perfect tense of «2476»; to be stationary, i.e. (figuratively) to persevere:--stand (fast).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to stand firm<LI>to persevere, to persist<LI>to keep one\'s standing</OL>'),
(4740, 'sthrigmovß', 'from (4741)', 'sterigmos', '7:653,1085', 'stay-rig-mos\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «4741»; stability (figuratively):--stedfastness.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>firm condition, steadfastness: of mind</OL>'),
(4741, 'sthrivzw', 'from a presumed derivative of (2476) (like (4731))', 'sterizo', '7:653,1085', 'stay-rid\'-zo', 'Verb', 'from a presumed derivative of «2476» (like «4731»); to set fast, i.e. (literally) to turn resolutely in a certain direction, or (figuratively) to confirm:--fix, (e-)stablish, stedfastly set, strengthen.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to make stable, place firmly, set fast, fix<LI>to strengthen, make firm<LI>to render constant, confirm, one\'s mind</OL>'),
(4742, 'stibavß', 'from a primary stizo (to \"stick\", i.e. prick)', 'stigma', '7:657,1086', 'stig\'-mah', 'Noun Neuter', 'from a primary stizo (to \"stick\", i.e. prick); a mark incised or punched (for recognition of ownership), i.e. (figuratively) scar of service:--mark.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a mark pricked in or branded upon the body. To ancient oriental usage, slaves and soldiers bore the name or the stamp of their master or commander branded or pricked (cut) into their bodies to indicate what master or general they belonged to, and there were even some devotee\'s who stamped themselves in this way with the token of their gods</OL>'),
(4743, 'stigmhv', 'from (4742)', 'stigme', 'None', 'stig-may\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'feminine of «4742»; a point of time, i.e. an instant:--moment.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>an instant (i.e. a moment) of time</OL>'),
(4744, 'stivlbw', 'apparently a primary verb', 'stilbo', '7:665,1087', 'stil\'-bo', 'Verb', 'apparently a primary verb; to gleam, i.e. flash intensely:--shining.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to shine, glisten<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of garments</OL></OL>'),
(4745, 'stoav', 'probably from (2476)', 'stoa', 'None', 'sto-ah\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'probably from «2476»; a colonnade or interior piazza:--porch.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a portico, a covered colonnade where people can stand or walk protected from the weather and the heat of the sun<LI>the portico built by Solomon in the eastern part of the temple (which in the temple\'s destruction by the Babylonians was left uninjured, and remained down to the time of King Agrippa, to whom the care of the temple was entrusted by the emperor Claudius, and who on account of its antiquity dare not demolish it and build anew.</OL>');
INSERT INTO `greek_lexicon` (`number`, `orig_word`, `word_orig`, `translit`, `tdnt`, `phonetic`, `part_of_speech`, `st_def`, `IPD_def`) VALUES
(4746, 'stoibavß', 'from a primary steibo (to \"step\" or \"stamp\")', 'stoibas', 'None', 'stoy-bas\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'from a primary steibo (to \"step\" or \"stamp\"); a spread (as if tramped flat) of loose materials for a couch, i.e. (by implication) a bough of a tree so employed:--branch.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>branch, leafy limb</OL>'),
(4747, 'stoicei\'on', 'from a presumed derivative of the base of (4748)', 'stoicheion', '7:670,1087', 'stoy-khi\'-on', 'Noun Neuter', 'neuter of a presumed derivative of the base of «4748»; something orderly in arrangement, i.e. (by implication) a serial (basal, fundamental, initial) constituent (literally), proposition (figuratively):--element, principle, rudiment.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>any first thing, from which the others belonging to some series or composite whole take their rise, an element, first principal<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>the letters of the alphabet as the elements of speech, not however the written characters, but the spoken sounds<LI>the elements from which all things have come, the material causes of the universe<LI>the heavenly bodies, either as parts of the heavens or (as others think) because in them the elements of man, life and destiny were supposed to reside<LI>the elements, rudiments, primary and fundamental principles of any art, science, or discipline<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>i.e. of mathematics, Euclid\'s geometry</OL></OL></OL>'),
(4748, 'stoicevw', 'from a derivative of steicho (to range in regular line)', 'stoicheo', '7:666,1087', 'stoy-kheh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from a derivative of steicho (to range in regular line); to march in (military) rank (keep step), i.e. (figuratively) to conform to virtue and piety:--walk (orderly).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to proceed in a row as the march of a soldier, go in order<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>metaph. to go on prosperously, to turn out well</OL><LI>to walk<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to direct one\'s life, to live</OL></OL>'),
(4749, 'stolhv', 'from (4724)', 'stole', '7:687,1088', 'stol-ay\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «4724»; equipment, i.e. (specially), a \"stole\" or long-fitting gown (as a mark of dignity):--long clothing (garment), (long) robe.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>an equipment<LI>an equipment in clothes, clothing<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>spec. a loose outer garment for men extending to the feet, worn by kings, priests, and persons of rank</OL></OL>'),
(4750, 'stovma', 'probably strengthened from a presumed derivative of the base of (5114)', 'stoma', '7:692,1089', 'stom\'-a', 'Noun Neuter', 'probably strengthened from a presumed derivative of the base of «5114»; the mouth (as if a gash in the face); by implication, language (and its relations); figuratively, an opening (in the earth); specially, the front or edge (of a weapon):--edge, face, mouth.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the mouth, as part of the body: of man, of animals, of fish, etc.<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>since thoughts of a man\'s soul find verbal utterance by his mouth, the \"heart\" or \"soul\" and the mouth are distinguished</OL><LI>the edge of a sword</OL>'),
(4751, 'stovmacoß', 'from (4750)', 'stomachos', 'None', 'stom\'-akh-os', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «4750»; an orifice (the gullet), i.e. (specially), the \"stomach\":--stomach.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the throat<LI>an opening, orifice, esp. of the stomach<LI>the stomach</OL>'),
(4752, 'strateiva', 'from (4754)', 'strateia', '7:701,1091', 'strat-i\'-ah', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «4754»; military service, i.e. (figuratively) the apostolic career (as one of hardship and danger):--warfare.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>an expedition, campaign, military service, warfare<LI>metaph. Paul likens his contest with the difficulties that oppose him in the discharge of his apostolic duties, as warfare</OL>'),
(4753, 'stravteuma', 'from (4754)', 'strateuma', '7:701,1091', 'strat\'-yoo-mah', 'Noun Neuter', 'from «4754»; an armament, i.e. (by implication) a body of troops (more or less extensive or systematic):--army, soldier, man of war.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>an army<LI>a band of soldiers<LI>bodyguard, guards men</OL>'),
(4754, 'strateuvw', 'middle voice from the base of (4756)', 'strateuomai', '7:701,1091', 'strat-yoo\'-om-ahee', 'Verb', 'middle voice from the base of «4756»; to serve in a military campaign; figuratively, to execute the apostolate (with its arduous duties and functions), to contend with carnal inclinations:--soldier, (go to) war(-fare).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to make a military expedition, to lead soldiers to war or to battle, (spoken of a commander)<LI>to do military duty, be on active service, be a soldier<LI>to fight</OL>'),
(4755, 'strathgovß', 'from the base of (4756) and (71) or (2233)', 'strategos', '7:701,1091', 'strat-ay-gos\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'from the base of «4756» and «71» or «2233»; a general, i.e. (by implication or analogy) a (military) governor (praetor), the chief (praefect) of the (Levitical) temple-wardens:--captain, magistrate.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the commander of an army<LI>in the NT a civic commander, a governor<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>the name the highest magistrate in the municipia or colonies; they had the power of administering justice in the less important cases<LI>of civil magistrates</OL><LI>captain of the temple, i.e. the commander of the Levites who kept guard in and around the temple</OL>'),
(4756, 'stratiav', 'from a derivative of stratos (an army from the base of (4766), as encamped)', 'stratia', '7:701,1091', 'strat-ee\'-ah', 'Noun Feminine', 'feminine of a derivative of stratos (an army; from the base of «4766», as encamped); camp-likeness, i.e. an army, i.e. (figuratively) the angels, the celestial luminaries:--host.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>an army, band of soldiers<LI>in the NT, the hosts of heaven<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>troops of angels<LI>the heavenly bodies, stars of heaven (so called on account of their number and their order)</OL></OL>'),
(4757, 'stratiwvthß', 'from a presumed derivative of the same as (4756)', 'stratiotes', '7:701,1091', 'strat-ee-o\'-tace', 'Noun Masculine', 'from a presumed derivative of the same as «4756»; a camper-out, i.e. a (common) warrior (literally or figuratively):--soldier.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a (common) soldier<LI>metaph. a champion of the cause of Christ</OL>'),
(4758, 'stratologevw', 'from a compound of the base of (4756) and (3004) (in its original sense)', 'stratologeo', '7:701,1091', 'strat-ol-og-eh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from a compound of the base of «4756» and «3004» (in its original sense); to gather (or select) as a warrior, i.e. enlist in the army:--choose to be a soldier.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to gather (collect) an army, to enlist soldiers<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of the commander</OL></OL>'),
(4759, 'from (4760) and (757)', 'Stratopedarches', 'stratopedarches', 'strat-op-ed-ar\'-khace', 'strat-op-ed-ar\'-khace', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the commander of a camp and army, a military tribune<LI>Praetorian prefect, commander of the praetorian cohorts, captain of the Roman emperor\'s body guard</OL>', 'from «4760» and «757»; a ruler of an army, i.e. (specially), a Praetorian praefect:--captain of the guard.', ''),
(4760, 'stratovpedon', 'from the base of (4756) and the same as (3977)', 'stratopedon', '7:701,1091', 'strat-op\'-ed-on', 'Noun Neuter', 'from the base of «4756» and the same as «3977»; a camping-ground, i.e. (by implication) a body of troops:--army.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a military camp<LI>soldiers in camp, an army</OL>'),
(4761, 'streblovw', 'from a derivative of (4762)', 'strebloo', 'None', 'streb-lo\'-o', 'Verb', 'from a derivative of «4762»; to wrench, i.e. (specially), to torture (by the rack), but only figuratively, to pervert:-- wrest.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to twist, turn awry<LI>to torture, put to the rack<LI>metaph. to pervert, of one who wrests or tortures language in a false sense</OL>'),
(4762, 'strevfw', 'strengthened from the base of (5157)', 'strepho', '7:714,1093', 'stref\'-o', 'Verb', 'strengthened from the base of «5157»; to twist, i.e. turn quite around or reverse (literally or figuratively):--convert, turn (again, back again, self, self about).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to turn, turn around<LI>to turn one\'s self (i.e. to turn the back to one<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of one who no longer cares for another)<LI>metaph. to turn one\'s self from one\'s course of conduct, i.e. to change one\'s mind</OL></OL>'),
(4763, 'strhniavw', 'from a presumed derivative of (4764)', 'streniao', 'None', 'stray-nee-ah\'-o', 'Verb', 'from a presumed derivative of «4764»; to be luxurious:--live deliciously.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to be wanton, to live luxuriously</OL>'),
(4764, 'strh\'noß', 'akin to (4731)', 'strenos', 'None', 'stray\'-nos', 'Noun Neuter', 'akin to «4731»; a \"straining\", \"strenuousness\" or \"strength\", i.e. (figuratively) luxury (voluptuousness):--delicacy.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>excessive strength which longs to break forth, over strength<LI>luxury<LI>eager desire</OL>'),
(4765, 'strouqivon', 'diminutive of strouthos (a sparrow)', 'strouthion', '7:730,1096', 'stroo-thee\'-on', 'Noun Neuter', 'diminutive of strouthos (a sparrow); a little sparrow:--sparrow.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a little bird, esp. of the sparrow sort, a sparrow</OL>'),
(4766, 'strwnnuvw', 'prolongation from a still simpler stroo {stro\'-o} (used only as an alternate in certain tenses, probably akin to (4731) through the idea of positing)', 'stronnumi', 'None', '', 'Verb', '(probably akin to «4731» through the idea of positing); to \"strew,\" i.e. spread (as a carpet or couch):--make bed, furnish, spread, strew.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to spread<LI>furnish<LI>to spread with couches or divans</OL>'),
(4767, 'stughtovß', 'from a derivative of an obsolete apparently primary stugo (to hate)', 'stugnetos', 'None', 'stoog-nay-tos\'', 'Adjective', 'from a derivative of an obsolete apparently primary stugo (to hate); hated, i.e. odious:--hateful.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>hated, detestable</OL>'),
(4768, 'stugnavzw', 'from the same as (4767)', 'stugnazo', 'None', 'stoog-nad\'-zo', 'Verb', 'from the same as «4767»; to render gloomy, i.e. (by implication) glower (be overcast with clouds, or sombreness of speech):--lower, be sad.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to be sad, sorrowful<LI>metaph. of the sky covered with clouds</OL>'),
(4769, 'stu\'loß', 'from stuo (to stiffen, properly akin to the base of (2476))', 'stulos', '7:732,1096', 'stoo\'-los', 'Noun Masculine', 'from stuo (to stiffen; properly akin to the base of «2476»); a post (\"style\"), i.e. (figuratively) support:--pillar.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a pillar<LI>a column<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>pillars of fire i.e. flames rising like pillars</OL><LI>a prop or support</OL>'),
(4770, 'Stwi>kovß', 'from (4745)', 'Stoikos', 'None', 'sto-ik-os\'', 'Adjective', 'from «4745»; a \"Stoic\" (as occupying a particular porch in Athens), i.e. adherent of a certin philosophy:--Stoick.', 'Stoics = \"of the portico\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>pertaining to the Stoic philosophy, the author of which, Zeno of Citium, taught at Athens</OL>'),
(4771, 'suv', 'the person pronoun of the second person singular', 'su', 'None', 'soo', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>you</OL>', 'the person pronoun of the second person singular; thou:-- thou. See also «4571», «4671», «4675»; and for the plural «5209», «5210», «5213», «5216».', ''),
(4772, 'suggevneia', 'from (4773)', 'suggeneia', '7:736,1097', 'soong-ghen\'-i-ah', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «4773»; relationship, i.e. (concretely) relatives:--kindred.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a kinship, relationship<LI>kindred, relations collectively, family</OL>'),
(4773, 'suggenhvß', 'from (4862) and (1085)', 'suggenes', '7:736,1097', 'soong-ghen-ace\'', 'Adjective', 'from «4862» and «1085»; a relative (by blood); by extension, a fellow countryman:--cousin, kin(-sfolk, -sman).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>of the same kin, akin to, related by blood<LI>in a wider sense, of the same nation, a fellow countryman</OL>'),
(4774, 'suggnwvmh', 'from a compound of (4862) and (1097)', 'suggnome', '1:716,119', 'soong-gno\'-may', 'Noun Feminine', 'from a compound of «4862» and «1097»; fellow knowledge, i.e. concession:--permission.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>pardon, indulgence</OL>'),
(4775, 'sugkavqhmai', 'from (4862) and (2521)', 'sugkathemai', 'None', 'soong-kath\'-ay-mahee', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «2521»; to seat oneself in company with:--sit with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to sit together, to sit with one another</OL>'),
(4776, 'sugkaqivzw', 'from (4862) and (2523)', 'sugkathizo', '7:787,1102', 'soong-kath-id\'-zo', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «2523»; to give (or take) a seat in company with:--(make) sit (down) together.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to cause to sit down together, place together<LI>to sit down together</OL>'),
(4777, 'sugkakopaqevw', 'from (4862) and (2553)', 'sugkakopatheo', '5:936,798', 'soong-kak-op-ath-eh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «2553»; to suffer hardship in company with:--be partaker of afflictions.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to suffer hardship together with one</OL>'),
(4778, 'sugkakoucevomai', 'from (4862) and (2558)', 'sugkakoucheo', 'None', 'soong-kak-oo-kheh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «2558»; to maltreat in company with, i.e. (passively) endure persecution together:--suffer affliction with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to treat ill with another<LI>to be ill treated in company with, share persecutions or come into a fellowship of ills</OL>'),
(4779, 'sugkalevw', 'from (4862) and (2564)', 'sugkaleo', '3:496,394', 'soong-kal-eh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «2564»; to convoke:--call together.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to call together, assemble<LI>to call together to one\'s self</OL>'),
(4780, 'sugkaluvptw', 'from (4862) and (2572)', 'sugkalupto', '7:743,1098', 'soong-kal-oop\'-to', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «2572»; to conceal altogether:--cover.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to cover on all sides, to conceal entirely, to cover up completely</OL>'),
(4781, 'sugkavmptw', 'from (4862) and (2578)', 'sugkampto', 'None', 'soong-kamp\'-to', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «2578»; to bend together, i.e. (figuratively) to afflict:--bow down.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to bend together, to bend completely<LI>metaph. to subject one to error and hardness of heart, a figure taken from bowing the back by captives compelled to pass under the yoke</OL>'),
(4782, 'sugkatabaivnw', 'from (4862) and (2597)', 'sugkatabaino', 'None', 'soong-kat-ab-ah\'-ee-no', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «2597»; to descend in company with:--go down with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to go down with<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of those who descend from a high place to a lower place as from Jerusalem to Caesarea</OL></OL>'),
(4783, 'sugkatavqesiß', 'from (4784)', 'sugkatathesis', 'None', 'soong-kat-ath\'-es-is', 'Verb', 'from «4784»; a deposition (of sentiment) in company with, i.e. (figuratively) accord with:--agreement.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a putting together or joint deposit (of votes)<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>hence approval, assent, agreement</OL></OL>'),
(4784, 'sugkatativqhmi', 'mid from (4862) and (2698)', 'sugkatatithemai', 'None', 'soong-kat-at-ith\'-em-ahee', 'Verb', 'mid from «4862» and «2698»; to deposit (one\'s vote or opinion) in company with, i.e. (figuratively) to accord with:--consent.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to deposit together with another<LI>to deposit one\'s vote in the urn with another<LI>to consent to, vote for, agree with</OL>'),
(4785, 'sugkatayhfivzomai', 'from (4862) and a compound of (2596) and (5585)', 'sugkatapsephizo', '9:604,*', 'soong-kat-aps-ay-fid\'-zo', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and a compound of «2596» and «5585»; to count down in company with, i.e. enroll among:--number with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>be depositing a ballot in the urn (i.e. by voting for) to assign one a place among, to vote one a place among<LI>to vote against with others, i.e. to condemn with others</OL>'),
(4786, 'sugkeravnnumi', 'from (4862) and (2767)', 'sugkerannumi', 'None', 'soong-ker-an\'-noo-mee', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «2767»; to commingle, i.e. (figuratively) to combine or assimilate:--mix with, temper together.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to mix together, commingle<LI>to unite<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>caused the several parts to combine into an organic structure, which is the body<LI>to unite one thing to another</OL></OL>'),
(4787, 'sugkinevw', 'from (4682) and (2795)', 'sugkineo', 'None', 'soong-kin-eh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4682» and «2795»; to move together, i.e. (specially), to excite as a mass (to sedition):--stir up.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to move together with others<LI>to throw into commotion, excite, stir up</OL>'),
(4788, 'sugkleivw', 'from (4862) and (2808)', 'sugkleio', '7:744,1098', 'soong-kli\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «2808»; to shut together, i.e. include or (figuratively) embrace in a common subjection to:--conclude, inclose, shut up.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to shut up together, enclose<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of a shoal of fishes in a net</OL><LI>to shut up on all sides, shut up completely</OL>'),
(4789, 'sugklhronovmoß', 'from (4862) and (2818)', 'sugkleronomos', '3:767 & 7:787,442 & 1102', 'soong-klay-ron-om\'-os', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «4862» and «2818»; a co-heir, i.e. (by analogy) participant in common:--fellow (joint)-heir, heir together, heir with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a fellow heir, a joint heir<LI>one who obtains something assigned to himself with others, a joint participant</OL>'),
(4790, 'sugkoinwnevw', 'from (4862) and (2841)', 'sugkoinoneo', '3:797,447', 'soong-koy-no-neh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «2841»; to share in company with, i.e. co-participate in:--communicate (have fellowship) with, be partaker of.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to become a partaker together with others, or to have fellowship with a thing</OL>'),
(4791, 'sugkoinwnovß', 'from (4862) and (2844)', 'sugkoinonos', '3:797,447', 'soong-koy-no-nos\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «4862» and «2844»; a co-participant:--companion, partake(-r, -r with).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>participant with others in anything, joint partner</OL>'),
(4792, 'sugkomivzw', 'from (4862) and (2865)', 'sugkomizo', 'None', 'soong-kom-id\'-zo', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «2865»; to convey together, i.e. collect or bear away in company with others:--carry.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to carry or bring together, to collect<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to house crops, gather into granaries</OL><LI>to carry with others, help in carrying out, the dead to be buried or burned<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to bury</OL></OL>'),
(4793, 'sugkrivnw', 'from (4862) and (2919)', 'sugkrino', '3:953,469', 'soong-kree\'-no', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «2919»; to judge of one thing in connection with another, i.e. combine (spiritual ideas with appropriate expressions) or collate (one person with another by way of contrast or resemblance):--compare among (with).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to joint together fitly, compound, combine<LI>to interpret<LI>to compare</OL>'),
(4794, 'sugkuvptw', 'from (4862) and (2955)', 'sugkupto', 'None', 'soong-koop\'-to', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «2955»; to stoop altogether, i.e. be completely overcome by:--bow together.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to bend completely forwards, to be bowed together</OL>'),
(4795, 'sugkuriva', 'from a comparative of (4862) and kureo (to light or happen', 'sugkuria', 'from the base of 2962)', 'soong-koo-ree\'-ah', 'Feminine Neuter', 'from a comparative of «4862» and kureo (to light or happen; from the base of «2962»); concurrence, i.e. accident:--chance.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>accident, by chance</OL>'),
(4796, 'sugcaivrw', 'from (4862) and (5463)', 'sugchairo', '9:359,1298', 'soong-khah\'-ee-ro', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «5463»; to sympathize in gladness, congratulate:--rejoice in (with).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to rejoice with, take part in another\'s joy<LI>to rejoice together, to congratulate</OL>'),
(4797, 'sugcevw', 'from (4862) and cheo (to pour) or its alternate', 'sugcheo', 'None', 'soong-kheh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and cheo (to pour) or its alternate; to commingle promiscuously, i.e. (figuratively) to throw (an assembly) into disorder, to perplex (the mind):--confound, confuse, stir up, be in an uproar.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to pour together, commingle<LI>to disturb the mind of one, to stir up to tumult or outbreak<LI>to confound or bewilder</OL>'),
(4798, 'sugcravomai', 'from (4862) and (5530)', 'sugchraomai', 'None', 'soong-khrah\'-om-ahee', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «5530»; to use jointly, i.e. (by implication) to hold intercourse in common:--have dealings with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to use with anyone, use jointly<LI>to associate with, to have dealings with</OL>'),
(4799, 'suvgcusiß', 'from (4797)', 'sugchusis', 'None', 'soong\'-khoo-sis', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «4797»; commixture, i.e. (figuratively) riotous disturbance:--confusion.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>confusion, disturbance<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of riotous persons</OL></OL>'),
(4800, 'suzavw', 'from (4862) and (2198)', 'suzao', '7:787,1102', 'sood-zah\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «2198»; to continue to live in common with, i.e. co-survive (literally or figuratively):--live with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to live together with one<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of physical life on earth<LI>to live a new life in union with Christ, i.e. dedicated to God</OL></OL>'),
(4801, 'suzeuvgnumi', 'from (4862) and the base of (2201)', 'suzeugnumi', 'None', 'sood-zyoog\'-noo-mee', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and the base of «2201»; to yoke together, i.e. (figuratively) conjoin (in marriage):--join together.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to fasten to one yoke, yoke together<LI>to join together unite<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of the marriage tie</OL></OL>'),
(4802, 'suzhtevw', 'from (4862) and (2212)', 'suzeteo', '7:747,1099', 'sood-zay-teh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «2212»; to investigate jointly, i.e. discuss, controvert, cavil:--dispute (with), enquire, question (with), reason (together).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to seek or examine together<LI>in the NT to discuss, dispute, question</OL>'),
(4803, 'suzhvthsiß', 'from (4802)', 'suzetesis', '7:748,1099', 'sood-zay\'-tay-sis', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «4802»; mutual questioning, i.e. discussion:--disputation(-ting), reasoning.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>mutual questioning, disputation, discussion</OL>'),
(4804, 'suzhththvß', 'from (4802)', 'suzetetes', '7:748,1099', 'sood-zay-tay-tace\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «4802»; a disputant, i.e. sophist:--disputer.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a disputer, i.e. a learned disputant, sophist</OL>'),
(4805, 'suvzugoß', 'from (4801)', 'suzugos', '7:748,1099', 'sood\'-zoo-gos', 'Adjective', 'from «4801»; co-yoked, i.e. (figuratively) as noun, a colleague; probably rather as a proper name; Syzygus, a Christian:--yokefellow.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>yoked together<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of those united by the bond of marriage, relationship, office, labour, study, business, or the like<LI>of a yoke fellow, consort, comrade, colleague, partner</OL></OL>'),
(4806, 'suzwopoievw', 'from (4862) and (2227)', 'suzoopoieo', '7:787,1102', 'sood-zo-op-oy-eh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «2227»; to reanimate conjointly with (figuratively):--quicken together with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to make one alive together<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of Christians, with Christ</OL></OL>'),
(4807, 'sukavminoß', 'of Hebrew origin (08256) in imitation of (4809)', 'sukaminos', '7:758,1100', 'soo-kam\'-ee-nos', 'Noun Feminine', 'of Hebrew origin («08256») in imitation of «4809»; a sycamore-fig tree:--sycamine tree.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>sycamine tree, having the form and foliage of the mulberry, but fruit resembling the fig</OL>'),
(4808, 'sukh\'', 'from (4810)', 'suke', '7:751,1100', 'soo-kay\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «4810»; a fig-tree:--fig tree.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a fig tree</OL>'),
(4809, 'sukomoreva', 'from (4810) and moron (the mulberry)', 'sukomoraia', '7:758,*', 'soo-kom-o-rah\'-yah', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «4810» and moron (the mulberry); the \"sycamore\"-fig tree:--sycamore tree. Compare «4807».', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a sycomore tree</OL>'),
(4810, 'su\'kon', 'apparently a primary word', 'sukon', '7:751,1100', 'soo\'-kon', 'Noun Neuter', 'apparently a primary word; a fig:--fig.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a fig, the ripe fruit of a fig tree</OL>'),
(4811, 'sukofantevw', 'from a compound of (4810) and a derivative of (5316)', 'sukophanteo', '7:759,1100', 'soo-kof-an-teh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from a compound of «4810» and a derivative of «5316»; to be a fig-informer (reporter of the law forbidding the exportation of figs from Greece), \"sycophant\", i.e. (genitive and by extension) to defraud (exact unlawfully, extort):--accuse falsely, take by false accusation.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to accuse wrongfully, to calumniate, to attack by malicious devices<LI>to exact money wrongfully<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to extort from, defraud</OL></OL>'),
(4812, 'sulagwgevw', 'from the base of (4813) and (the reduplicated form of) (71)', 'sulagogeo', 'None', 'soo-lag-ogue-eh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from the base of «4813» and (the reduplicated form of) «71»; to lead away as booty, i.e. (figuratively) seduce:--spoil.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to carry off booty<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to carry one off as a captive (and slave)<LI>to lead away from the truth and subject to one\'s sway</OL></OL>'),
(4813, 'sulavw', 'from a derivative of sullo (to strip, probably akin to (138), cf (4661))', 'sulao', 'None', 'soo-lah\'-o', 'Verb', 'from a derivative of sullo (to strip; probably akin to «138»; compare «4661»); to despoil:--rob.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to rob, despoil</OL>'),
(4814, 'sullalevw', 'from (4862) and (2980)', 'sullaleo', 'None', 'sool-lal-eh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «2980»; to talk together, i.e. converse:--commune (confer, talk) with, speak among.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to talk with</OL>'),
(4815, 'sullambavnw', 'from (4862) and (2983)', 'sullambano', '7:759,1101', 'sool-lam-ban\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «2983»; to clasp, i.e. seize (arrest, capture); specially, to conceive (literally or figuratively); by implication, to aid:--catch, conceive, help, take.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to seize, take: one as prisoner<LI>to conceive, of a woman<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>metaph. of lust whose impulses a man indulges</OL><LI>to seize for one\'s self<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>in a hostile sense, to make (one a permanent) prisoner</OL><LI>to take hold together with one, to assist, help, to succour</OL>'),
(4816, 'sullevgw', 'from (4862) and (3004) in its original sense', 'sullego', 'None', 'sool-leg\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «3004» in its original sense; to collect:--gather (together, up).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to gather up<LI>to collect in order to carry off</OL>'),
(4817, 'sullogivzomai', 'from (4862) and (3049)', 'sullogizomai', 'None', 'sool-log-id\'-zom-ahee', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «3049»; to reckon together (with oneself), i.e. deliberate:--reason with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to bring together accounts, reckon up, compute<LI>to reckon with one\'s self, to reason</OL>'),
(4818, 'sullupevw', 'from (4862) and (3076)', 'sullupeo', '4:323,*', 'sool-loop-eh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «3076»; to afflict jointly, i.e. (passive) sorrow at (on account of) someone:--be grieved.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to affect with grief together<LI>give with one\'s self</OL>'),
(4819, 'sumbaivnw', 'from (4862) and the base of (939)', 'sumbaino', 'None', 'soom-bah\'-ee-no', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and the base of «939»; to walk (figuratively, transpire) together, i.e. concur (take place):--be(-fall), happen (unto).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to walk with the feet near together<LI>to come together, meet with one<LI>of things which fall out at the same time, to happen, turn out, come to pass</OL>'),
(4820, 'sumbavllw', 'from (4862) and (906)', 'sumballo', 'None', 'soom-bal\'-lo', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «906»; to combine, i.e. (in speaking) to converse, consult, dispute, (mentally) to consider, (by implication) to aid, (personally) to join, attack:--confer, encounter, help, make, meet with, ponder.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to throw together, to bring together<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to converse<LI>to bring together in one\'s mind, confer with one\'s self<LI>to come together, meet<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to encounter in a hostile sense<LI>to fight with one<LI>to bring together of one\'s property, to contribute, aid, help</OL></OL></OL>'),
(4821, 'sumbasileuvw', 'from (4862) and (936)', 'sumbasileuo', '1:591 & 7:787,1102', 'soom-bas-il-yoo\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «936»; to be co-regent (figuratively):--reign with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to reign together<LI>metaph. to possess supreme honour, liberty, blessedness, with one in the kingdom of God</OL>'),
(4822, 'sumbibavzw', 'from (4862) and bibazo (to force, causative [by reduplication] of the base of (939))', 'sumbibazo', '7:763,1101', 'soom-bib-ad\'-zo', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and bibazo (to force; causative (by reduplication) of the base of «939»); to drive together, i.e. unite (in association or affection), (mentally) to infer, show, teach:--compact, assuredly gather, intrust, knit together, prove.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to cause to coalesce, to join together, put together<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to unite or knit together: in affection</OL><LI>to put together in one\'s mind<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to compare<LI>to gather, conclude, consider</OL><LI>to cause a person to unite with one in a conclusion or come to the same opinion, to prove, demonstrate<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to teach, instruct, one</OL></OL>'),
(4823, 'sumbouleuvw', 'from (4862) and (1011)', 'sumbouleuo', 'None', 'soom-bool-yoo\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «1011»; to give (or take) advice jointly, i.e. recommend, deliberate or determine:--consult, (give, take) counsel (together).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to give counsel<LI>to take counsel with others, take counsel together, to consult, deliberate</OL>'),
(4824, 'sumbouvlion', 'from a presumed derivative of (4825)', 'sumboulion', 'None', 'soom-boo\'-lee-on', 'Noun Neuter', 'neuter of a presumed derivative of «4825»; advisement; specially, a deliberative body, i.e. the provincial assessors or lay-court:--consultation, counsel, council.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>counsel, which is given, taken, entered upon<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>consult, deliberate</OL><LI>a council<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>an assembly of counsellors or persons in consultation (the governors and procurators of provinces had a board of assessors or advisers with whom they took council before rendering judgment)</OL></OL>'),
(4825, 'suvmbouloß', 'from (4862) and (1012)', 'sumboulos', 'None', 'soom\'-boo-los', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «4862» and «1012»; a consultor, i.e. adviser:--counsellor.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>an adviser, counsellor</OL>'),
(4826, 'Sumewvn', 'from the same as (4613)', 'Sumeon', 'None', 'soom-eh-one\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'from the same as «4613»; Symeon (i.e. Shimon), the name of five Israelites:--Simeon, Simon.', 'Simon = \"harkening\"<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the second son of Jacob by Leah<LI>one of Abraham\'s descendants<LI>the one who took the infant Jesus in his arms in the temple<LI>a teacher at the church of Antioch<LI>the original name of Peter the apostle</OL>'),
(4827, 'summaqhthvß', 'from a compound of (4862) and (3129)', 'summathetes', '4:460,552', 'soom-math-ay-tace\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'from a compound of «4862» and «3129»; a co-learner (of Christianity):--fellow disciple.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a fellow disciple</OL>'),
(4828, 'summarturevw', 'from (4862) and (3140)', 'summartureo', '4:508,564', 'soom-mar-too-reh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «3140»; to testify jointly, i.e. corroborate by (concurrent) evidence:--testify unto, (also) bear witness (with).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to bear witness with, bear joint witness</OL>'),
(4829, 'summerivzw', 'middle voice from (4862) and (3307)', 'summerizomai', 'None', 'soom-mer-id\'-zom-ahee', 'Verb', 'middle voice from «4862» and «3307»; to share jointly, i.e. participate in:--be partaker with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to divide at the same time, divide together<LI>to assign a portion<LI>to divide together with one (so that a part comes to me, a part to him)</OL>'),
(4830, 'summevtocoß', 'from (4862) and (3353)', 'summetochos', '2:830,286', 'soom-met\'-okh-os', 'Adjective', 'from «4862» and «3353»; a co-participant:--partaker.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>partaking together with one, a joint partaker<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of something</OL></OL>'),
(4831, 'summimhthvß', 'from a presumed compound of (4862) and (3401)', 'summimetes', '4:659,594', 'soom-mim-ay-tace\'', 'Noun Masculine', 'from a presumed compound of «4862» and «3401»; a co-imitator, i.e. fellow votary:--follower together.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>an imitator of others</OL>'),
(4832, 'summorfivzw', 'from (4862) and (3444)', 'summorphos', '7:787,1102', 'soom-mor-fos\'', 'Adjective', 'from «4862» and «3444»; jointly formed, i.e. (figuratively) similar:--conformed to, fashioned like unto.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>having the same form as another, similar, conformed to</OL>'),
(4833, 'summorfovw', 'from (4832)', 'summorphoo', '7:787,*', 'soom-mor-fo\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4832»; to render like, i.e. (figuratively) to assimilate:--make conformable unto.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to be conformed to, receive the same form as</OL>'),
(4834, 'sumpaqevw', 'from (4835)', 'sumpatheo', '5:935,798', 'soom-path-eh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4835»; to feel \"sympathy\" with, i.e. (by implication) to commiserate:--have compassion, be touched with a feeling of.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to be affected with the same feeling as another, to sympathise with<LI>to feel for, have compassion on</OL>'),
(4835, 'sumpaqhvß', 'from (4841)', 'sumpathes', '5:935,798', 'soom-path-ace\'', 'Adjective', 'from «4841»; having a fellow-feeling (\"sympathetic\"), i.e. (by implication) mutually commiserative:--having compassion one of another.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>suffering or feeling the like with another, sympathetic</OL>'),
(4836, 'sumparagivnomai', 'from (4862) and (3854)', 'sumparaginomai', 'None', 'soom-par-ag-in\'-om-ahee', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «3854»; to be present together, i.e. to convene; by implication, to appear in aid:--come together, stand with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to come together<LI>to come to one\'s help</OL>'),
(4837, 'sumparakalevw', 'from (4862) and (3870)', 'sumparakaleo', 'None', 'soom-par-ak-al-eh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «3870»; to console jointly:--comfort together.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to call upon or invite or exhort at the same time or together<LI>to strengthen (comfort) with others</OL>'),
(4838, 'sumparalambavnw', 'from (4862) and (3880)', 'sumparalambano', 'None', 'soom-par-al-am-ban\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «3880»; to take along in company:--take with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to take along together with<LI>in the NT to take with one as a companion</OL>'),
(4839, 'sumparamevnw', 'from (4862) and (3887)', 'sumparameno', 'None', 'soom-par-am-en\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «3887»; to remain in company, i.e. still live:--continue with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to abide together with<LI>to continue to live together</OL>'),
(4840, 'sumpavreimi', 'from (4862) and (3918)', 'sumpareimi', 'None', 'soom-par\'-i-mee', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «3918»; to be at hand together, i.e. now present:--be here present with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to be present together</OL>'),
(4841, 'sumpavscw', 'from (4862) and (3958) (including its alternate)', 'sumpascho', '5:925 & 7:787,798 & 1102', 'soom-pas\'-kho', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «3958» (including its alternate); to experience pain jointly or of the same kind (specially, persecution; to \"sympathize\"):--suffer with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to suffer or feel pain together<LI>to suffer evils (troubles, persecutions) in the like manner with another</OL>'),
(4842, 'sumpevmpw', 'from (4862) and (3992)', 'sumpempo', 'None', 'soom-pem\'-po', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «3992»; to despatch in company:--send with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to send together with</OL>'),
(4843, 'sumperilambavnw', 'from (4862) and a compound of (4012) and (2983)', 'sumperilambano', 'None', 'soom-per-ee-lam-ban\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and a compound of «4012» and «2983»; to take by enclosing altogether, i.e. earnestly throw the arms about one:--embrace.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to comprehend at once<LI>to embrace completely</OL>'),
(4844, 'sumpivnw', 'from (4862) and (4095)', 'sumpino', 'None', 'soom-pee\'-no', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «4095»; to partake a beverage in company:--drink with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to drink with</OL>'),
(4845, 'sumplhrovw', 'from (4862) and (4137)', 'sumpleroo', '6:308,867', 'soom-play-ro\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «4137»; to implenish completely, i.e. (of space) to swamp (a boat), or (of time) to accomplish (passive, be complete):--(fully) come, fill up.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to fill completely<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of the hold of a ship</OL><LI>to complete entirely, be fulfilled: of time</OL>'),
(4846, 'sumpnivgw', 'from (4862) and (4155)', 'sumpnigo', '6:455,895', 'soom-pnee\'-go', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «4155»; to strangle completely, i.e. (literally) to drown, or (figuratively) to crowd:--choke, throng.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to choke utterly<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>metaph. the seed of the divine word sown in the mind<LI>to press round or throng one so as almost to suffocate him</OL></OL>'),
(4847, 'sumpolivthß', 'from (4862) and (4177)', 'sumpolites', 'None', 'soom-pol-ee\'-tace', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «4862» and «4177»; a native of the same town, i.e. (figuratively) co-religionist (fellow-Christian):--fellow- citizen.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>possessing the same citizenship with others, a fellow citizen<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of Gentiles as received into communion of the saints<LI>of the people consecrated to God</OL></OL>'),
(4848, 'sumporeuvomai', 'from (4862) and (4198)', 'sumporeuomai', 'None', 'soom-por-yoo\'-om-ahee', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «4198»; to journey together; by implication, to assemble:--go with, resort.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to go or journey together<LI>to come together, to assemble</OL>'),
(4849, 'sumpovsion', 'from a derivative of the alternate of (4844)', 'sumposion', 'None', 'soom-pos\'-ee-on', 'Noun Neuter', 'neuter of a derivative of the alternate of «4844»; a drinking-party (\"symposium\"), i.e. (by extension) a room of guests:--company.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a drinking party, entertainment<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of the party itself, the guests<LI>rows of guests</OL></OL>'),
(4850, 'sumpresbuvteroß', 'from (4862) and (4245)', 'sumpresbuteros', '6:651,931', 'soom-pres-boo\'-ter-os', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «4862» and «4245»; a co-presbyter:--presbyter, also an elder.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a fellow elder</OL>'),
(4851, 'sumfevrw', 'from (4862) and (5342) (including its alternate)', 'sumphero', '9:69,1252', 'soom-fer\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «5342» (including its alternate); to bear together (contribute), i.e. (literally) to collect, or (figuratively) to conduce; especially (neuter participle as a noun) advantage:--be better for, bring together, be expedient (for), be good, (be) profit(-able for).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to bear or bring together<LI>to bear together or at the same time<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to carry with others<LI>to collect or contribute in order to help<LI>to help, be profitable, be expedient</OL></OL>'),
(4852, 'suvmfhmi', 'from (4862) and (5346)', 'sumphemi', 'None', 'soom\'-fay-mee', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «5346»; to say jointly, i.e. assent to:--consent unto.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to consent, confess</OL>'),
(4853, 'sumfulevthß', 'from (4862) and a derivative of (5443)', 'sumphuletes', 'None', 'soom-foo-let\'-ace', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «4862» and a derivative of «5443»; a co-tribesman, i.e. native of the same country:--countryman.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>one who is of the same people, a fellow countryman</OL>'),
(4854, 'suvmfutoß', 'from (4862) and a derivative of (5453)', 'sumphutos', '7:786,1102', 'soom\'-foo-tos', 'Adjective', 'from «4862» and a derivative of «5453»; grown along with (connate), i.e. (figuratively) closely united to:--planted together.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>born together with, of joint origin<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>connate, congenital, innate, implanted by birth or nature</OL><LI>grown together, united with<LI>kindred</OL>'),
(4855, 'sumfuvw', 'from (4862) and (5453)', 'sumphuo', 'None', 'soom-foo\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «5453»; passive, to grow jointly:--spring up with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to cause to grow together<LI>to grow together, grow with</OL>'),
(4856, 'sumfwnevw', 'from (4859)', 'sumphoneo', '9:304,1287', 'soom-fo-neh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4859»; to be harmonious, i.e. (figuratively) to accord (be suitable, concur) or stipulate (by compact):--agree (together, with).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to agree together<LI>to agree with one in making a bargain, to make an agreement, to bargain</OL>'),
(4857, 'sumfwvnhsiß', 'from (4856)', 'sumphonesis', '9:304,1287', 'soom-fo\'-nay-sis', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «4856»; accordance:--concord.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>concord, agreement</OL>'),
(4858, 'sumfwniva', 'from (4859)', 'sumphonia', '9:304,1287', 'soom-fo-nee\'-ah', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «4859»; unison of sound (\"symphony\"), i.e. a concert of instruments (harmonious note):--music.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>music</OL>'),
(4859, 'suvmfwnoß', 'from (4862) and (5456)', 'sumphonos', '9:304,1287', 'soom\'-fo-nos', 'Adjective', 'from «4862» and «5456»; sounding together (alike), i.e. (figuratively) accordant (neuter as noun, agreement):-- consent.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>harmonious, accordant, agreeing<LI>thing agreed upon, compact</OL>'),
(4860, 'sumyhfivzw', 'from (4862) and (5585)', 'sumpsephizo', '9:604,1341', 'soom-psay-fid\'-zo', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «5585»; to compute jointly:--reckon.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to compute, count up<LI>to vote with one</OL>'),
(4861, 'suvmyucoß', 'from (4862) and (5590)', 'sumpsuchos', 'None', 'soom\'-psoo-khos', 'Adjective', 'from «4862» and «5590»; co-spirited, i.e. similar in sentiment:--like-minded.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>of one mind, of one accord</OL>This word is made up of two words \"sun\" (together with) and psuchos(soul, self, inner life, or the seat of the feelings, desires,affections). So the word refers to being united in spirit orharmonious (A&G). Paul desired the Philippians to be united intheir affections - one in Christ in all desires! Used only herein the NT. - Wayne Steury'),
(4862, 'suvn', 'a primary preposition denoting union', 'sun', '7:766,1102', 'soon', 'Preposition', 'a primary preposition denoting union; with or together (but much closer than «3326» or «3844»), i.e. by association, companionship, process, resemblance, possession, instrumentality, addition, etc.:--beside, with. In composition it has similar applications, including completeness.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>with</OL>'),
(4863, 'sunavgw', 'from (4862) and (71)', 'sunago', 'None', 'soon-ag\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «71»; to lead together, i.e. collect or convene; specially, to entertain (hospitably):--+ accompany, assemble (selves, together), bestow, come together, gather (selves together, up, together), lead into, resort, take in.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to gather together, to gather<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to draw together, collect<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>of fishes<LI>of a net in which they are caught</OL></OL><LI>to bring together, assemble, collect<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to join together, join in one (those previously separated)<LI>to gather together by convoking<LI>to be gathered i.e. come together, gather, meet</OL><LI>to lead with one\'s self<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>into one\'s home, i.e. to receive hospitably, to entertain</OL></OL>'),
(4864, 'sunagwghv', 'from (the reduplicated form of) (4863)', 'sunagoge', '7:798,1108', 'soon-ag-o-gay\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'from (the reduplicated form of) «4863»; an assemblage of persons; specially, a Jewish \"synagogue\" (the meeting or the place); by analogy, a Christian church:--assembly, congregation, synagogue.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a bringing together, gathering (as of fruits), a contracting<LI>in the NT, an assembling together of men, an assembly of men<LI>a synagogue<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>an assembly of Jews formally gathered together to offer prayers and listen to the reading and expositions of the scriptures; assemblies of that sort were held every sabbath and feast day, afterwards also on the second and fifth days of every week; name transferred to an assembly of Christians formally gathered together for religious purposes<LI>the buildings where those solemn Jewish assemblies are held. Synagogues seem to date their origin from the Babylonian exile. In the times of Jesus and the apostles every town, not only in Palestine, but also among the Gentiles if it contained a considerable number of Jewish inhabitants, had at least one synagogue, the larger towns several or even many. These were also used for trials and inflicting punishment.</OL></OL>'),
(4865, 'sunagwnivzomai', 'from (4862) and (75)', 'sunagonizomai', 'None', 'soon-ag-o-nid\'-zom-ahee', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «75»; to struggle in company with, i.e. (figuratively) to be a partner (assistant):--strive together with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to strive together with one, to help one in striving</OL>'),
(4866, 'sunaqlevw', 'from (4862) and (118)', 'sunathleo', '1:167,25', 'soon-ath-leh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «118»; to wrestle in company with, i.e. (figuratively) to seek jointly:--labour with, strive together for.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to strive at the same time with another</OL>'),
(4867, 'sunaqroivzw', 'from (4862) and athroizo (to hoard)', 'sunathroizo', 'None', 'soon-ath-royd\'-zo', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and athroizo (to hoard); to convene:--call (gather) together.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to gather together with others<LI>to assemble<LI>to be gathered together i.e. to come together</OL>'),
(4868, 'sunaivrw', 'from (4862) and (142)', 'sunairo', 'None', 'soon-ah\'-ee-ro', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «142»; to make up together, i.e. (figuratively) to compute (an account):--reckon, take.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to take up together with another or others<LI>to bring together with others<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to cast up or settle accounts<LI>to make a reckoning with</OL></OL>'),
(4869, 'sunaicmavlwtoß', 'from (4862) and (164)', 'sunaichmalotos', '1:195,31', 'soon-aheekh-mal\'-o-tos', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «4862» and «164»; a co-captive:--fellowprisoner.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a fellow prisoner</OL>'),
(4870, 'sunakolouqevw', 'from (4862) and (190)', 'sunakoloutheo', '1:216,33', 'soon-ak-ol-oo-theh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «190»; to accompany:--follow.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to follow together with others, to accompany</OL>'),
(4871, 'sunalivzw', 'from (4862) and halizo (to throng)', 'sunalizo', 'None', 'soon-al-id\'-zo', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and halizo (to throng); to accumulate, i.e. convene:--assemble together.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to gather together, assemble<LI>to be assembled, meet with</OL>'),
(4872, 'sunanabaivnw', 'from (4862) and (305)', 'sunanabaino', 'None', 'soon-an-ab-ah\'-ee-no', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «305»; to ascend in company with:--come up with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to ascend at the same time, come up together with to a higher place<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>with one</OL></OL>'),
(4873, 'sunanavkeimai', 'from (4862) and (345)', 'sunanakeimai', '3:654,425', 'soon-an-ak\'-i-mahee', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «345»; to recline in company with (at a meal):--sit (down, at the table, together) with (at meat).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to recline together, feast together<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of guests</OL></OL>'),
(4874, 'sunanamivgnumi', 'from (4862) and a compound of (303) and (3396)', 'sunanamignumi', '7:852,1113', 'soon-an-am-ig\'-noo-mee', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and a compound of «303» and «3396»; to mix up together, i.e. (figurative) associate with:--(have, keep) company (with).', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to mix up together<LI>to keep company with, be intimate with one</OL>'),
(4875, 'sunanapauvomai', 'middle from (4862) and (373)', 'sunanapauomai', 'None', 'soon-an-ap-ow\'-om-ahee', 'Verb', 'middle from «4862» and «373»; to recruit oneself in company with:--refresh with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to take rest together with<LI>to sleep together with, to lie with<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of a husband and wife<LI>metaph. to rest or refresh one\'s spirits with one (i.e. to give and get refreshment by mutual intercourse)</OL></OL>'),
(4876, 'sunantavw', 'from (4862) and a derived from (473)', 'sunantao', 'None', 'soon-an-tah\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and a derivative of «473»; to meet with; figuratively, to occur:--befall, meet.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to meet with<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of events: to happen or befall</OL></OL>'),
(4877, 'sunavnthsiß', 'from (4876)', 'sunantesis', 'None', 'soon-an\'-tay-sis', 'Noun Feminine', 'from «4876»; a meeting with:--meet.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a meeting with</OL>'),
(4878, 'sunantilambavnomai', 'from (4862) and (482)', 'sunantilambanomai', '1:375,62', 'soon-an-tee-lam-ban\'-om-ahee', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «482»; to take hold of opposite together, i.e. co-operate (assist):--help.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to lay hold along with, to strive to obtain with others, help in obtaining<LI>to take hold with another</OL>'),
(4879, 'sunapavgw', 'from (4862) and (520)', 'sunapago', 'None', 'soon-ap-ag\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «520»; to take off together, i.e. transport with (seduce, passively, yield):--carry (lead) away with, condescend.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to lead away with or together<LI>metaph. to be carried away with<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of a thing, i.e. by a thing, so as to experience with others the force of that which carries away<LI>to yield or submit one\'s self to lowly things, conditions, employments: not to evade their power</OL></OL>'),
(4880, 'sunapoqnh/vskw', 'from (4862) and (599)', 'sunapothnesko', '3:7 & 7:786,312 & 1102', 'soon-ap-oth-nace\'-ko', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «599»; to decease (literally) in company with, or (figuratively), similarly to:--be dead (die) with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to die together<LI>to die with one</OL>'),
(4881, 'sunapovllumi', 'from (4862) and (622)', 'sunapollumi', 'None', 'soon-ap-ol\'-loo-mee', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «622»; to destroy (middle voice or passively, be slain) in company with:--perish with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to destroy together<LI>to perish together (to be slain along with)</OL>');
INSERT INTO `greek_lexicon` (`number`, `orig_word`, `word_orig`, `translit`, `tdnt`, `phonetic`, `part_of_speech`, `st_def`, `IPD_def`) VALUES
(4882, 'sunapostevllw', 'from (4862) and (649)', 'sunapostello', 'None', 'soon-ap-os-tel\'-lo', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «649»; to despatch (on an errand) in company with:--send with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to send with</OL>'),
(4883, 'sunarmologevw', 'from (4862) and a derivative of a compound of (719) and (3004) (in its original sense of laying)', 'sunarmologeo', '7:855,1114', 'soon-ar-mol-og-eh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and a derivative of a compound of «719» and «3004» (in its original sense of laying); to render close-jointed together, i.e. organize compactly:--be fitly framed (joined) together.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to join closely together<LI>to frame together<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>parts of a building<LI>the members of the body</OL></OL>'),
(4884, 'sunarpavzw', 'from (4862) and (726)', 'sunarpazo', 'None', 'soon-ar-pad\'-zo', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «726»; to snatch together, i.e. seize:--catch.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to seize by force<LI>to catch or lay hold of (one so that he is no longer his own master)<LI>to seize by force and carry away</OL>'),
(4885, 'sunauxavnw', 'from (4862) and (837)', 'sunauxano', 'None', 'soon-owx-an\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «837»; to increase (grow up) together:--grow together.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to cause to grow together<LI>to grow together</OL>'),
(4886, 'suvndesmoß', 'from (4862) and (1199)', 'sundesmos', '7:856,1114', 'soon\'-des-mos', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «4862» and «1199»; a joint tie, i.e. ligament, (figuratively) uniting principle, control:--band, bond.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>that which binds together, a band, bond<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>of ligaments by which the members of the human body are united together</OL><LI>that which is bound together, a bundle</OL>'),
(4887, 'sundevw', 'from (4862) and (1210)', 'sundeo', 'None', 'soon-deh\'-o', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «1210»; to bind with, i.e. (passively) be a fellow-prisoner (figuratively):--be bound with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to tie together, to bind together<LI>to bind or fasten on all sides<LI>to bind just as (i.e. jointly with) another</OL>'),
(4888, 'sundoxavzw', 'from (4862) and (1392)', 'sundoxazo', '2:253 & 7:787,178 & 1102', 'soon-dox-ad\'-zo', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «1392»; to exalt to dignity in company (i.e. similarly) with:--glorify together.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to approve together, to join in approving<LI>to glorify together</OL>'),
(4889, 'suvndouloß', 'from (4862) and (1401)', 'sundoulos', '2:261,182', 'soon\'-doo-los', 'Noun Masculine', 'from «4862» and «1401»; a co-slave, i.e. servitor or ministrant of the same master (human or divine):--fellowservant.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a fellow servant, one who serves the same master with another<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>the associate of a servant (or slave)<LI>one who with others serves (ministers to) a king<LI>a colleague of one who is Christ\'s servant in publishing the gospel<LI>one who with others acknowledges the same Lord, Jesus, and obeys his commands<LI>one who with others is subject to the same divine authority in the Messianic economy<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>of angels as the fellow servants of Christians</OL></OL></OL>'),
(4890, 'sundromhv', 'from (the alternate of) (4936)', 'sundrome', 'None', 'soon-drom-ay\'', 'Noun Feminine', 'from (the alternate of) «4936»; a running together, i.e. (riotous) concourse:--run together.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>a running together, concourse, esp. hostile or riotous</OL>'),
(4891, 'sunegeivrw', 'from (4862) and (1453)', 'sunegeiro', '7:786,1102', 'soon-eg-i\'-ro', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «1453»; to rouse (from death) in company with, i.e. (figuratively) to revivify (spirtually) in resemblance to:--raise up together, rise with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to raise together, to cause to raise together<LI>to raise up together from mortal death to a new and blessed life dedicated to God</OL>'),
(4892, 'sunevdrion', 'from a presumed derivative of a compound of (4862) and the base of (1476)', 'sunedrion', '7:860,1115', 'soon-ed\'-ree-on', 'Noun Neuter', 'neuter of a presumed derivative of a compound of «4862» and the base of «1476»; a joint session, i.e. (specially), the Jewish Sanhedrin; by analogy, a subordinate tribunal:--council.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>any assembly (esp. of magistrates, judges, ambassadors), whether convened to deliberate or pass judgment<LI>any session or assembly or people deliberating or adjudicating<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>the Sanhedrin, the great council at Jerusalem, consisting of the seventy one members, viz. scribes, elders, prominent members of the high priestly families and the high priest, the president of the assembly. The most important causes were brought before this tribunal, inasmuch as the Roman rulers of Judaea had left to it the power of trying such cases, and also of pronouncing sentence of death, with the limitation that a capital sentence pronounced by the Sanhedrin was not valid unless it was confirmed by the Roman procurator.<LI>a smaller tribunal or council which every Jewish town had for the decision of less important cases.</OL></OL>'),
(4893, 'suneivdhsiß', 'from a prolonged form of (4894)', 'suneidesis', '7:898,1120', 'soon-i\'-day-sis', 'Noun Feminine', 'from a prolonged form of «4894»; co-perception, i.e. moral consciousness:--conscience.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>the consciousness of anything<LI>the soul as distinguishing between what is morally good and bad, prompting to do the former and shun the latter, commending one, condemning the other<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>the conscience</OL></OL>'),
(4894, 'sunei\'don', 'from (4862) and (1492)', 'suneido', '7:898,*', 'soon-i\'-do', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «1492»; to see completely; used (like its primary) only in two past tenses, respectively meaning to understand or become aware, and to be conscious or (clandestinely) informed of:--consider, know, be privy, be ware of.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to see (have seen) together with others<LI>to see (have seen) in one\'s mind with one\'s self<OL TYPE=\"a\"><LI>to understand, perceive, comprehend,</OL><LI>to know with another<LI>to know in one\'s mind or with one\'s self, to be conscience of</OL>'),
(4895, 'suvneimi', 'from (4862) and (1510) (including its various inflections)', 'suneimi', 'None', 'soon\'-i-mee', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and «1510» (including its various inflections); to be in company with, i.e. present at the time:--be with.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to be with</OL>'),
(4896, 'suvneimi', 'from (4862) and eimi (to go)', 'suneimi', 'None', 'soon\'-i-mee', 'Verb', 'from «4862» and eimi (to go); to assemble:--gather together.', '<OL TYPE=\"1\"><LI>to come together</OL>'),
